<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Beats China Anew in World Volleyball League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- World top-notched Italy fought off
tough challenge to beat China 15-11, 17-15, 15-6 for its second
victory in two days at the World Volleyball League Group B
preliminaries here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
China, who lost the first with three indentical 15-6 on
Saturday, once seemed to boast of a different squad overnight by
surging ahead 6-1 through fierce attacks from ace spiker Zhang
Xiang and new face An Jiajie.
</P>
<P>
However, its advatage was evaperated soon when Italy, two-time
world champion and World Cup holder, pulled back for 8-7 with five
consecutive spikes from 26-year-old Andrea Sartoretti.
</P>
<P>
Trailed again at 8-9, the Italians managed for 11-11 before
winning the first set 15-11.
</P>
<P>
The second set featured even more thrilling moments as both
sides exchanged lead six times and the Italians became the hard
nuts by winning two decisive points from 15-15 with two solid
blocks in front of a fervant home crowd.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese nationals lost their rhythm in the third set,
succumbing 15-6 to the visitors, who won the world league
champions five times but finished second last year.
</P>
<P>
"The game of tonight is much better than yesterday. They were
good in receiving our serves, and it became difficult for us to
stop them attacking," said Italian head coach Bebeto de Freitas,
who replaced Argentine Julio Velasco early this year to take helm
of the squad.
</P>
<P>
Freitas explained that his disciples spared no efforts and had
done the best when they trailed in the scoreboard. "They had
played very hard from the very beginning, even at the moment we
were in the most difficult situation."
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Wang Jiawei, a former national who led China
to a record fifth berth in the World Cup tournament, said: "I told
our players not to fear in attacks because our rival is the world
champion, we have nothing to lose."
</P>
<P>
Freitas, who had coached his native Brazilian national squad
for 10 years, tigtened his lips on whether he could live up to the
legend Velasco had written since 1989.
</P>
<P>
Under Velasco's guidance, Italy had won almost all the major
titles in international volleyball arena except an Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
"It is a completely different team. The players are very young
and they have a long way to go," Freitas said.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the Brazilian had a glittering slate during his over
15-year coaching stint. He helped Brazil win second place in both
1982 World Championships in Argentina and 1984 Olympics in Los
Angeles, and also led Italy's Palma club to win both the national
championship and European Championships.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the professional league in Italy resulted in
the great success for their men spikers in the past decade. "I
have no doubt that the pro league is the solution, which provides
stiff competiton for the spikers off the international season," he
said.
</P>
<P>
China, who was bracketed in Group B with Italy, Yugoslavia and
Spain, had played both Yugoslavia and Spain twice each on the
road, only to be defeated in all six outings.
</P>
<P>
Teams from 12 countries and regions compete in the World League
in three groups. Each team plays six home-and-away matches through
June 22. The two top teams from each group will advance to the
final round scheduled on June 30 in Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
