<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Mkapa Concludes Visit to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa
left here this afternoon for Harare, Zimbabwe after a four-day
state visit to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, he said that east Africa will become a
single investment and trade destination whereby the movement of
people, capital and goods will be unrestricted.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian head of state urged Kenyan business community to
do more investments in his country as Tanzania has changed the
environment to make it attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his country has adopted a liberalized market
economy to boost her financial status and privatized her economy
which is in the process of phasing out Ujamaa public investment
strategies.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa who led a trade delegation told Kenyan
businessmen that the east African leaders are not intending to
create a large market for foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
"We want to create a large market primarily for good quality
goods produced within the region by well-managed and
well-distributed industries," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa asked the private sectors in the three east African
countries to mobilize their forces to guard the region from being
converted into a dumping ground for cheap foreign imports.
</P>
<P>
The president toured various development projects in Nairobi,
Athi River and Kiambu District, and attended this year's Madaraka
Day celebrations held this morning in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
In a signed article, the daily newspapers Sunday Times today
said that Mkapa's visit and his presence at the Madaraka Day
celebrations signified the excellent relations between Kenya and
Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
