<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Forms Women's Peace Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU) today approved the establishment of the African Women
Committee on Peace.
</P>
<P>
African ministers proposed the formation at their
just-concluded meeting which preceded the OAU's 33rd summit due
to open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said there was need to establish a concrete
mechanism to facilitate the participation of women in the
continent's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Most African countries, in pursuance of the Global Platform
for Action, endorsed during the 1995 International Women's
Conference in Beijing various programs to enhance women's
participation in politics and development.
</P>
<P>
African ministers "recognize the important role and
contribution of women in the promotion of peace," a statement
issued at the meeting of African ministers said.
</P>
<P>
The statement called upon OAU member states and other relevant
organizations to encourage and popularize the culture of peace
and tolerance in all sectors of the African society.
</P>
<P>
The meeting required OAU member states to submit to the OAU
secretariat regular reports on the implementation of the Africa
platform for action in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
The ministers entrusted OAU Secretary General Salim Ahmed
Salim to convene a pan-African conference of ministers
responsible for women's matters to coordinate women's issues into
the development agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ciller to Become Turkish Prime Minister This Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Tansu
Ciller announced here today that she will become prime minister
before the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
This means that the chairwoman of the True Path Party (DYP)
will take over power from Necmettin Erbakan, leader of the Welfare
Party (RP) in the coalition government, one year ahead of schedule
set in a bi-partite agreement.
</P>
<P>
The RP and DYP formed the coalition government in 1996 and
signed the power-sharing protocol which stipulated that Erbakan
would head the government for the first two years and then turn it
over to Ciller for the remaining two years.
</P>
<P>
Ciller made the announcement of her early-than-scheduled
premiership at a joint press conference with Necmettin Erbakan,
the incumbent prime minister, after their talks.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan told reporters that his RP and the DYP have agreed on
early elections but the two sides will continue to work out an
exact date.
</P>
<P>
After 11 months in power, the coalition government is now faced
with growing impatience with Erbakan's inclination to inch the
country toward an Islamic entity and his reluctance to curb the
fundamentalist force in the country.
</P>
<P>
The military and opposition regarded Erbakan' policies as a
threat to Turkey's secularism enshrined in its constitution.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, under the increasing pressure from within here party,
had asked Erbakan to transfer the premiership and agree on early
elections in one year.
</P>
<P>
Some DYP parliamentary deputies dissatisfied with Cillar's
weak attitude toward the senior coalition partner RP, had
threatened to withdraw from the party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Reports Progress in Egypt's Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel reported progress in
today's meeting between Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
and Egyptian peace envoy Osama Baz, who is mediating a resumption
of the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Netanyahu's office said that at the
meeting some progress had been made toward solving the problems
between Israel and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA). But
it did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Baz, senior adviser to Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, who is on the second shuttle mission in the past
week, would continue contacts between the two sides, although no
date was set for his next meeting with Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Baz returned to the Egyptian capital of Cairo late today after
meeting with Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, the Egyptian envoy said he was not
satisfied with the results of his current mission, but he would
continue his efforts to save the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Following the Netanyahu-Mubarak summit held in Egypt's Red Sea
resort Sharm el-Sheikh last Tuesday, Israel agreed to grant Egypt
the role of mediator in the Israeli-Palestinian disputes.
</P>
<P>
Baz began his first shuttle mission earlier last week,
meeting separately with Netanyahu and PNA President Yasser
Arafat in an attempt to arrange a three-way summit to break the
ice in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today before meeting with Baz, Netanyahu voiced
cautious optimism about the Egyptian efforts to revive the peace
march.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with four Israeli lawmakers who have
recently met with Arafat, Netanyahu expressed the belief that
Egypt's efforts would achieve the goal of resuming the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
According to Yehud Lankri, who was among the four lawmakers,
Netanyahu at the same time cautioned against the so-called Arafat
attempt to split Israel's public opinion and the ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
The four lawmakers are reportedly working to arrange a summit
between Netanyahu, Mubarak and Jordanian King Hussein, or
Moroccan King Hassan II. The Moroccan king has so far refused to
meet with Netanyahu since the Israeli leader came to power one
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Erekat told Israel Radio that as long as the
Israeli government continues its settlement activities, there is
no hope for the resumption of the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"So far the Israeli government insists on continuing
settlement activities, I think the gap between the two sides is
much bigger than others think," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Netanyahu must stop, must freeze the settlement activities,
if he wants to give the peace process a chance, if he wants to
have negotiations that have meaning and credibility," Erekat
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Food Aid Convoy Attacked in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Somali gunmen attacked and
hijacked a World Food Program convoy transporting food aid in
north Mogadishu yesterday afternoon, said a report available here
today.
</P>
<P>
The convoy consisting of three lorries of ground maize and
cooking oil were attacked by unidentified technical vehicles near
the Green Line while crossing to the south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitnesses, the gunmen on board the battle
wagons had fired warning shots before succeeding to snatch two of
the food aid transporting lorries and moved them into the former
Italian embassy where the militiamen maintain a base in north
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The report also said the guards of the convoy did not return
fire and as a result no casualties was caused by the incident.
</P>
<P>
The food aid, which was part of 1,500 tons of food consisting
of lentils, maize-mill and cooking oil provided by the WFP, was
allocated to disabled former military personnel in the Martini
Military Hospital of south Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
WFP local staff members in Mogadishu refused to make any
comment about the hijacked food convoy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
