<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Attacks Qatar On Issue of Economic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel today reacted angrily to
the position taken by Qatar regarding the forthcoming Middle
East and North African Economic Summit, according to a report
of the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed official was quoted by the radio as saying that the
statements by the Qatari foreign minister at the end of the
two-day meeting of the six Gulf Arab foreign ministers in Doha
constituted a sign of what he called "hostile environment which
is not conducive to the regional cooperation."
</P>
<P>
In response to a question on Israel's participation in the
November summit, the Qatari foreign minister reportedly replied
that, if there are improvements in the stalemated peace process
and changes of Israeli hardline position, then it will be possible
to extend invitation to Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli official reacted by saying that, while such
statements are aimed at pressuring Israel, in fact, they serve to
hurt the chances of success of the conference.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the question is not whether eventually
Netanyahu or Israel is invited, but whether there is an
atmosphere conducive to economic cooperation in the Middle East
and North Africa by important businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Qatar and Oman are two GCC (Gulf Cooperation Council) members
to have economic ties with the Jewish state. The other four
members, Saudi Arabia, The United Arab Emirates, Kuwait and
Bahrain have made no attempt to forge formal links with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel opened its trade office in Doha on May 26, 1996; Qatar
has so far not reciprocated.
</P>
<P>
Qatar is under pressure from other GCC and Arab League
states to break off all economic relations with Israel, under
a resolution of the Arab League foreign ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israel hopes that, instead of being canceled, the conference
will be set at ministerial level as was the case in
Cairo last year, rather than inviting heads of government as
at Casablanca in 1994 and Amman in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
