<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Appeals for OAU Financial Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Liberia, cash-strapped and
war-torn, today appealed for African and international assistance
to enable it to hold post-civil war elections re-scheduled for
July 9.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Foreign Minister Monie Captan, who is here for the
Organization of African Unity's summit, told reporters that
Liberia had secured 60 percent of the required funds for the
elections postponed from May 30.
</P>
<P>
"We are appealing to the OAU and international community to
provide some assistance to cover the remaining aspects of the
budget," Captan said.
</P>
<P>
He said part of reason the elections had been postponed was to
allow the participation of hundreds of thousands of refugees
scattered in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"Getting international support for the conduct of elections is
the most important thing at the moment," said Captan.
</P>
<P>
He commended the support his country received from the OAU
since the ethnic fighting flared up in 1989.
</P>
<P>
He said Liberia was among Africa's success stories of
effective conflict resolution by the OAU.
</P>
<P>
The OAU will hold its 33rd summit next week to strengthen,
among other things, its mechanism for conflict prevention,
management and resolution in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
