<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Gets Quarter of Supply in 6 Months: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iraqi official said that
Iraq has received only a quarter of the food supply bought by the
country under the "oil-for-food" deal, even though it has
completed its limited oil sale.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here today, Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed
Mehdi Saleh told reporters that since the "oil-for-food" deal came
into force last December, Iraq has received 700,000 tonnes of
food, 28 percent of a total of 2.4 million tonnes to be bought by
the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that up till now, no Iraqis have received all the
basket supply under the present ration system, which includes a
monthly amount of 9 kilograms of wheat flour, 2.5 kilograms of
rice, a kilogram of sugar and a small amount of other daily
necessities.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi trade minister also complained of the discontinuity
of the delivery of food to Iraq. He held the U.S. responsible for
this situation.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, a spokesman of the Iraqi Trade Ministry said that
the amount of food distribution to the Iraqis will have to be
reduced next month because the U.S. representative in the
U.N. sanctions committee had canceled several contracts for rice
provision signed by Iraq with foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Saleh stressed that in the past six months, about 30,000 Iraqi
children died as a result of delayed delivery of supplies to Iraq,
medicine and medical instruments in particular.
</P>
<P>
"Medicine should have arrived in Iraq to save the lives of
these children, they are the victims of the ill-policy against
Iraq adopted by the U.S. government," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister claimed that there is what he termed as
discrimination in approving the contracts signed by Iraq and
foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Some contracts for food and medicine have been approved, but
other similar contracts have been canceled, said Saleh, calling
the "oil-for-food" deal a "political program rather than a
humanitarian one."
</P>
<P>
When asked by Xinhua about how Iraq will respond if the
U.N. puts forward a proposal to extend the deal for another six
months, Saleh said what Iraq wants is to normalize its oil export
and to have the sanctions lifted without any delay.
</P>
<P>
He said that the fact is neither the U.N. has raised such a
proposal nor the Iraqi government has asked for extension.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is
expected to put forward a proposal whether the deal will be
extended or not.
</P>
<P>
Iraq declared on Friday that it has completed selling 120
million barrels of oil, the total amount sanctioned for sale in
accordance with the "oil-for-food" deal.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which will expire June 9, allows Iraq to sell 1
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over six months to buy food,
medicine and other goods urgently needed in the country hit by
stringent sanctions after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Jiawei Depicts Patriotism with Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- To many Chinese, the name of Wang
Jiawei is closely linked to patriotism.
</P>
<P>
As an ace spiker, he paced the Chinese national team to an
epoch-making fifth spot in the World Cup in 1981, which earned him
a nickname of "Airman of the net."
</P>
<P>
By giving up his scholarship in Japan, he backed home without
hesitation in 1986, helping China retain the title at Seoul Asian
Games with a broken finger.
</P>
<P>
And again when the national squad downgraded to a record low,
he hesitated nothing to put aside envious pay in Japan, coming
back to shoulder the task of head coach in April.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks after taking the helm, he realized the real gap
between China and the world's first-class teams. The newly-formed
team lost six consecutive matches in the World League Group B
preiminaries, twice each to Spain, Yugoslavia and Italy.
</P>
<P>
But Wang was confident. "Let's do it step by step. We had
learned a lot from the losses."
</P>
<P>
In their sixth game against world top-ranked Italy in Beijing
on Sunday, the Chinese spikers staged tenacious challenge to the
visitors, only dropping the home game 15-12, 15-15, 15-6 after the
thrilling first two sets.
</P>
<P>
The surprising performance arouse a great hope of renaissance
of China's volleyball in the minds of the enthusiastic fans across
the country.
</P>
<P>
However, it needed courage to face the challenge as a head
coach since China never won an Asian title after 1990. Everyone
bears the fear of spoiling his coaching career if he fails to
bring the national team out of the shadow.
</P>
<P>
Only Wang keeps his firm determination to swim agaisnt the tide.
</P>
<P>
Behind all this, it was scrafice, earnest love for the country,
and responsiblity for the volleyball team.
</P>
<P>
"It has long been my dream to become head coach. Now I finally
have the opportunity to do something for the motherland," Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
Wang revealed that he cherishes a three-sponged project -- to
reclaimed the title at the Asian championships in September, and
to make breakthroughs in Asian Games and World Championships next
year.
</P>
<P>
To achieve these goals, Wang believes, every player under his
charge firstly must be clear that everything they do is done for
the country.
</P>
<P>
Before the team left for Spain for the World League tournament,
he led the players to Tiananmen Square, watching the
national-flag-raising ceremony at dawn.
</P>
<P>
"Patriotism is not a blank word. It should be shown in concrete
action," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
In March 20, 1981, the Chinese team, spearheaded by Wang, made
a storming surge in the World Cup preliminaries in Hong Kong, won
three consecutive sets from two sets down and ensured a World Cup
berth.
</P>
<P>
Students in Beijing University, excited after watching the
thriller on TV, took to the streets by thousands and put forward
the best-known slogan "United to rejuvenate China," which has been
encouraging the Chinese people especially the youths.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen years later, some 500 students from Beijing University
paid the homage to the game on Sunday by taking half an hour on
bus. A thunderous cheer was occasionally echoed overhead at the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
"The slogan has been carved in a stele in our campus. It has
become a motto of students in Beijing University, " said Wu Lijun,
a chemistry postgraduate. "They gave a boost to a whole generation
one decade ago. Now we should give them cheers when they are in an
all-time low."
</P>
<P>
Recalling the legend 16 years ago, Wang said:"I think it should
be still useful to all the Chinese people after such a long time."
</P>
<P>
Italy's coach Bebeto de Freitas, who knew Wang in the early
1980s, also expressed great admiration for his counterpart.
</P>
<P>
"He is determined to contribute for China's volleyball. It's
not a measure of money, It needs passion."
</P>
<P>
Freitas, who described Wang as one of the best players he had
seen in his life, cherished the belief that Wang will make great
changes to China's volleyball. "Not only the players, but the
whole China will take him as an example," the Brazlian said.
</P>
<P>
Some people, who were eager but found no way to go aboard for
gold rush, were bemused by Wang's act to return home.
</P>
<P>
"This is my only dream," he said. "I love men's volleyball team
of China, I should do something for it. That's my responsibility,"
Wang explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
