<HEADLINE> Turkey to Hold Early Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the two parties in
Turkey's coalition government said here today that they had agreed
to hold early elections but failed to fix the exact date.
</P>
<P>
This was announced at a joint press conference by Welfare Party
(RP) Chairman and Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan, and True Path
Party (DYP) leader and Deputy Prime Minister Tansu Ciller.
</P>
<P>
The two partner parties in the government will continue to
jointly work out a date for the early elections, Erbakan said
after his 45-minute-long talks with Ciller.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said the exact date for the early elections will be
announced within the first two weeks of this months and a report
will be submitted to the Turkish parliament for approval as soon
as possible, said Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Cillar announced that she will take over the
premiership from Erbakan in the second half of this month, a year
ahead of the schedule set in a power-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
The RP and DYP signed the bi-partite protocol in June 1996 which
stipulated that Erbakan would head the government for the first
two years and then turn it over to Ciller for the remaining two
years.
</P>
<P>
After 11 months in power, the coalition government is now
faced with growing impatience with Erbakan's Islamic tendency,
regarded by the military and opposition as a serious threat to
Turkey's secularism enshrined in its constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
