<HEADLINE> (URGENT) French Left Wins Legislative Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The French leftwing parties have won
333 seats in the 577-seat parliament, beating the outgoing
center-right coalition and imposing a cohabitation upon President
Jacques Chirac, according to primary estimations.
</P>
<P>
After the second round of the legislative elections, the
Socialist Party has won 290 seats, the Communist Party 35 seats
and the Greens eight seats, said the primary estimation by the CSA
polling institute, France-3 television station and Radio France
published at 20:00 (1800 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The center-right Gaullist Rally for the Republic and Union of
French Democracy won 242 seats, losing more than 220 seats from
its former parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
The extreme National Front party won two seats and entered the
parliament for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Another estimation by the SOFRES polling institute, TF1
television station and RTL radio station said that the Socialist
Party has won 289 seats, the Communist Party 36 seats and the
Greens eight.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party alone has won an absolute majority of more
than 289 seats and can form a government, according to the two
estimations.
</P>
<P>
A third estimation by the BVA polling institute said that the
Socialist Party has won 274 seats, the Communists 36 seats, and
the Greens eight seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
