<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Plays Pivotal Role in Peace Process, US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. diplomat to Egypt
reiterated today Egypt's role is pivotal in pushing forward the
Mideast peace process and in removing obstacles facing peace in
the region.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Mohammed Abdullah, head of the
People's Assembly External Relations Committee, the U.S.
Ambassador to Cairo Edward Walker said the enormous efforts
exerted by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak are highly respected
and appreciated by the U.S. and global public opinion.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt plays a pivotal role in accelerating the Mideast peace
process," the Egyptian Middle East news agency (MENA) quoted him
as saying.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Abdullah urged the U.S., co-sponsor of the peace
process, to play a mightier role to restart the peace talks that
became stalled when Israel began building a new Jewish settlement
in Har Homa of Arab East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
"People of the region expect the U.S. to salvage the peace
process as the main sponsor of peace and the only one capable of
influencing Israel to abide by the terms of reference of the
peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. envoy Dennis Ross made two shuttle trips to the region
last month, but failed to bridge the gap between the Palestinian
and Israeli sides.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians accused Ross of pro-Israeli bias and called
for higher-level U.S. intervention. But Washington was not
responsive.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said last weekend
that it was up to the two parties to show the political will to
end the impasse themselves.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Jordan and Egypt both affirmed the importance of
the U.S. role in the peace-making.
</P>
<P>
Intensive Egyptian diplomatic efforts to revive the deadlocked
Mideast peace process climaxed last Tuesday when Hosni Mubarak
met with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu in the
Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian envoy Osama el-Baz went to Israel today to continue
talks with Netanyahu at the beginning of another shuttle tour
mediating between Israelis and Palestinians in a bid to bring
them back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Baz, political advisor to the Egyptian president, is expected
to meet later today with head of the Palestinian negotiating team
Saeb Erekat. He has been shuttling between the two sides since
Tuesday's summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
