<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Parties Against Foreign Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean political parties
have urged foreign countries to stay away and let the country
settle its own problems arising from the May 25 military coup, a
report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The country's All Political Parties Association (APPA), in a
broadcast message on Saturday, said "Sierra Leone must be left
alone to resolve the present internal political crisis".
</P>
<P>
The message signed by APPA's Secretary-General Victor Foh
"condemns attempts by foreign countries to interfere in the
internal affairs of Sierra Leone".
</P>
<P>
The APPA is an umbrella organization of Sierra Leone's 12
political parties, including the Sierra Leonean People's Party of
ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Its message comes amid wild speculations of imminent
intervention by countries in the west African sub-region, which
insist on restoring the government of elected president Kabbah,
in case of failed peaceful resolution through diplomatic
channels.
</P>
<P>
The APPA message applauded "the current peace overtures put in
place by the Armed Forces Revolutionary Council", which was set
up by Major Paul Jonny Koromah after the coup as the highest
ruling body.
</P>
<P>
The parties also urged the defense forces to observe the law
and co-operate with the Sierra Leonean forces, the police, the
AFRC and the rebel Revolutionary United Front in pursuit of
peace, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
