<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Left Victory in France Changes Europe's Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The victory of French left parties in
the legislative elections has changed the political scenery of
Europe overnight and will alter more or less the agenda of
European integration made by President Jacques Chirac and
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany.
</P>
<P>
After the British Labor Party won the general election on May
1, the French Socialist Party, a "sister party" of the British
Labor, carried off the legislative elections called one year
earlier by President Chirac in a gamble to win a new center-right
majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party and other leftwing parties have won 333
seats in the 577-seat French National Assembly after two rounds of
voting, according to primary estimations by French media
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Chirac's gamble thus turned out to be a disastrous
miscalculation and backfired by imposing a left government upon
himself, forcing him to cohabit, or share power with his political
opponents at a time deemed decisive for the launching of the
European single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
Socialist chief Lionel Jospin, who will be the next prime
minister of France, will surely overhaul many of the austerity
socio-economic plans adopted by Alain Juppe, the prime minister
until today, which were aimed at cutting public spending to meet
the criteria of the Maastricht treaty to qualify for the euro.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party promises to create 700,000 jobs, half of
them in state enterprises, cut work week from 39 hours to 35 hours
without reducing salary, and stop the privatization process of
some state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, if the next leftwing government is joined by the
Communist Party, which completely rejects the Maastricht treaty
and opposes privatization, more unpopular policies of the former
government are likely to be rejected.
</P>
<P>
According to primary estimations, the Socialist Party alone can
form a parliamentary majority and establish a leftwing government
with some smaller moderate leftwing parties.
</P>
<P>
Although the Socialist Party does not oppose the European
single currency, it is against the policy of attaining budgetary
criteria for joining the euro at heavy social costs as was adopted
by the former government.
</P>
<P>
As unemployment stays at 12.8 percent and social discontent
remains high, the French voters have revolted against the policy
of Prime Minister Alain Juppe over the past two years and urged a
radical change of policy, which is promised by the Socialists.
</P>
<P>
The left victory in France has also coincided with the rise of
doubt in Germany over the capability of the government to launch
the euro, as the German leftwing parties are also expected to
challenge the ruling majority of Chancellor Kohl in next year's
general election.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Germany Social-Democratic Party Oskar Lafontaine
jointly issued a declaration last week with French Socialist
leader Jospin calling for the inclusion of a social clause in the
Maastricht treaty.
</P>
<P>
The gesture indicates that the leftist forces of continental
Europe are not content with the American-style free market theory
and want to keep the social tradition of the old continent built
over the past century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
