<HEADLINE> Ghanaian Troops Leave for Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- An unspecific number of Ghanaian
soldiers left Accra, capital of Ghana, this morning for Sierra
Leone to help evacuate some 1,000 Ghanaians from the troubled
country in the wake of last Sunday's coup.
</P>
<P>
The commander of the Ghanaian continent will also be involved
in the negotiations for a political settlement of the crisis in
Sierra Leone, the Nigeria Television Authority (NTA) reported.
</P>
<P>
After that, the Ghanaian soldiers may be deployed to help
stabilize the situation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, Ghana's Deputy
Foreign Minister Victor Gbeho has been recalled from Harare,
Zimbabwe, where he was attending the current summit of the
Organization of African Unity, to join the negotiation team of
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
The NTA reported that although the work of the team has been
95 percent completed, the possibility of military intervention
can not be ruled out as Major Johnny Koroma has declared himself
chairman of the current ruling council.
</P>
<P>
Reports also said that Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings has
cancelled his trip to Harare for the OAU summit in order to
monitor the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the coup that overthrew Sierra Leone's elected
government led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah closed the
country's borders on Thursday night after the accelerated efforts
of some Western countries to evacuate their nationals.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. helicopters are reported to come back to the capital
Freetown today for evacuating more expatriates in a hotel guarded
by soldiers of the ECOWAS peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The reports estimated there are about 3,000 ECOMOG soldiers in
Freetown ready for a possible military intervention for restoring
Kabbah's government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
