<HEADLINE> Bombing Case Jurors Recess Without Verdict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Jurors in the Oklahoma City
bombing trial of Timothy McVeigh in Denver, Colorado, recessed
without a verdict today after a shortened third day of
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
The panelists, who have been behind closed doors for a total of
19 hours since Friday, were told from the beginning they could set
their own hours and decided to cut their work short at noon today.
</P>
<P>
Before sending them back to their hotel, U.S. District Judge
Richard Match warned them again not to discuss the case and to
avoid news reports, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
The seven-man, five-woman jury is considering murder and
conspiracy charges against McVeigh in the April 19, 1995 bombing
that killed 168 people. McVeigh, 29, could get the death penalty
if convicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
