<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's privatization program has increased net
profitability by 500 percent for public business sector companies
since it was carried out six years ago, the latest issue of the
Egyptian daily Al-Ahram reported.
</P>
<P>
Atef Ebeid, Egyptian minister of public business sector and
minister of state for administrative development, said these
companies' profit soared from 8.5 billion Egyptian pounds (2.5
billion U.S. dollars) to 50 billion pounds (14.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Abdul Hamid Ibrahim, chairman of the Money Market
Authority has said Arab and foreign investments are extremely
active in the Egyptian Stock Exchange, according to the latest
Egyptian daily Al-Ahram.
</P>
<P>
The concrete dealings on the Egyptian capital market from
March 1996 to the end of May 1997 amounted to 5 billion pounds
(1.47 billion dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
The stocks which have been circulated from January to May in
1997, were valued at 10,110 billion pounds (2,973 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A total of some 300,000 Egyptians working in Jordan
should either obtain valid work permits or leave the country with
the current exemption of fines as of last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed between Jordan and Egypt in
March, from April 1 on, all Egyptian workers found in violation
will be deported or face legal actions by Jordan's Labor Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment among the Jordanians is largely due to those who
shun jobs (which are then) taken by non-Jordanians," said
Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali on May 18 while
meeting Minister of Labor Saleh Khasawneh.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 Egyptian are working in Jordan and most of them
illegally, according to officials here.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The European Union (EU) has decided to offer Syria
31 million European Currency Units (equivalent to 34.1 million
U.S. dollars) in financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
The aid will be used to boost Syrian communications and
tourism, and modernize municipalities of major Syrian cities
suffering from growing population, sources at the EU Commission
in Damascus said today.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total amount, 11 million dollars will be earmarked
to financing the communications sector, 19.8 million dollars to
modernizing the municipalities of four Syrian cities with high
population density; and the rest to developing the tourism
sector.
</P>
<P>
The EU is to give this financial assistance to Syria within
the EU-Mediterranean partnership agreement concluded at the
first EU-Med conference held in Barcelona of Spain in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
