<HEADLINE> Serial Israeli Air Raids Kill Lebanese Civilian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- One civilian was killed and four
others wounded in a series of air strikes launched by Israeli
fighter-bombers in south Lebanon this evening, the state-run
Lebanon Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli jets carried out the first air raid at 4:30 p.m.
(1330 GMT) at suspected guerrilla targets on the hill of Telal
Mlita on the heights of Iglim Al-Toffah, or Province of
Apple, some 60 kilometers southeast of Beirut, the radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli warplanes flew back and launched the second raid
on the vicinities of Majdal Salim at 5:45 p.m. (1445 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Four air-to-surface missiles fired by the warplanes exploded
some 200 meters away from the residence of the village's chief
Islamic cleric, Imam Ahmad Shawqi Amin, killing one person and
wounded four others, the radio said, without specifying whether
the Imam was among the victims.
</P>
<P>
An hour later, the Israeli fighters rocketed the same
place on the outskirts of Majdal Salim, destroying an
ambulance of the Lebanese Islamic Health Organization, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for the Israeli aggression, guerrillas of the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, launched several attacks
at positions of the Israeli troops in the Israeli
self-proclaimed "security zone" in south Lebanon, the report
said, without mentioning casualties. Enitem


