<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Secretary of State Visits Sarajevo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright today held talks with Bosnian leaders, pushing them to
comply with the Washington-brokered Dayton peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Albright met the three members of the Bosnian presidency,
Muslim chairman Alija Izetbegovic, Serb member Momocilo Krajsnik
and Croat member Kresimir Zubak, shortly after she arrived in
Sarajevo for a one-day visit to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the meeting, the Permanent Committee for Bosnian
Military Matters, which consists of officers from all three ethnic
armies, was set up, according Bosnian Foreign Minister Jadranko
Prilic.
</P>
<P>
Prilic said that the committee would deal with state security
and the implementation of arms reduction provisions of the Dayton
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Sarajevo, Albright said that
Washington would condition its assistance on their compliance with
the Dayton accords, especially on those of returning refugees and
building common institutions.
</P>
<P>
If Bosnian authorities failed to act on U.S. demands "to knit
the multi-ethnic society together, then there will not be American
assistance," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
She also said that the hanging around of the persons accused by
an international court as war criminals was "the major roadblock"
to the Bosnian peace process, but gave no clear indication as how
Washington is going to remove it.
</P>
<P>
Albright later flew to Brcko, a town in the Serb entity, to
attend a re-opening ceremony of a bridge there which connects
Bosnia with Croatia.
</P>
<P>
She also addressed NATO American soldiers stationed in the
Brcko area before flying to Banja Luka for a meeting with Biljana
Plavsic, president of the Serb republic entity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
