<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong To Embrace New Era: Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, who will become
chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) of China in four weeks' time, said here today that July 1
would be the beginning of a new era rather than the summary of a
phase of history.
</P>
<P>
In a 50-minute interview televised live on local circuit, the
HKSAR's chief executive reaffirmed his confidence in the future of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The return of Hong Kong to its motherland is a historic affair
for the Chinese nation. The day of July 1 bears great significance
for Chinese people living in Hong Kong," Tung said at the start of
the interview with six local radios and televisions.
</P>
<P>
At that moment, Hong Kong people will no longer be the Chinese
residents under British colonial rule, but dignified Chinese
people, said the Chief Executive.
</P>
<P>
"After the handover, Hong Kong will be closely related with the
inland areas not only in terms of economic links, but also in
terms of culture and ties of blood. We and the inland compatriots
share the same origin," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Judging by his contact with China's leaders, Tung believed that
the Chinese government is determined to fully implement the
principle of "one country, two systems", so as to maintain the
continued prosperity of Hong Kong after the handover.
</P>
<P>
He cited the latest opinion poll, which showed that more than
80 percent of Hong Kong citizens were optimistic about the future
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
As a further evidence, a recent survey conducted by the three
largest foreign chambers of commerce in Hong Kong -- Japanese,
American and British chambers -- showed that 90 percent of their
members saw a rosy picture of the investment environment in Hong
Kong over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Having been elected as the HKSAR's first Chief Executive for
more than five months, Tung reviewed his work in preparation for
the establishment of the first HKSAR government, mainly the
formation of the executive, legislative and judicial
administration.
</P>
<P>
Tung also touched on the livelihood issues Hong Kong residents
are concerned with, such as housing, education and welfare for the
 elderly. He promised to announce specific policies as soon as
possible after he assumes office.  
</P>
</TEXT>
