<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homicides Plunge in New York City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- New York City, the largest city of
the United States, has been listed as the the most safe city among
big cities with over 1 million population in this country as the
city saw homicides plunged 14 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The city recorded the number of homicides dropping to 966 in
1996 from 1,177 in 1995, according to figures released Sunday by
the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the city recorded fewer than 1,000
killings in the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
Homicide is considered the most accurately measured crime in
this country, and also the one that Americans fear most.
</P>
<P>
And the percentage of murder cases cleared by the New York City
Police Department last year was higher than it had been in
decades. The figure is in stark contrast to the national trend,
which has seen clearance rates plummet over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
A series of factors that contributed to the sharp decrease in
murder cases in New York include innovative police tactics,
tougher Federal gun control laws, a stabilization of the drug
trade and the aging of the baby boom population which has passed
out of its prime years for committing crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
