<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gains in US Income, Spending Slow in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The personal income growth in
the U.S. slowed sharply in April, a further indication that the
U.S. economy is decelerating from its quick pace at the beginning
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department reported today that the personal
income rose just 0.1 percent in April, the smallest increase since
last October.
</P>
<P>
The small increase also resulted in a slow consumer spending
increase. The consumer spending edged up only by 0.1 percent in
April, the smallest since last September.
</P>
<P>
The 0.1 percent rise in incomes followed much bigger gains of
0.6 percent in March, 0.8 percent in February, 0.4 percent in
January and 0.7 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
Private wages and salaries, which had been rising at an annual
rate of 26 billion dollars in March, decreased by 4.2 billion in
April, reflecting a drop in average weekly hours worked and
average hourly earnings.
</P>
<P>
The personal savings as a percentage of disposable income held
steady at 5.1 percent in the month, the same as in March.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the 0.1 percent increase in spending in
April followed a revised 0.2 percent spending increase in March.
The small March advance represented a sharp downward revision from
an original estimate of 0.5 percent, indicating purchases were not
nearly as strong as first believed.
</P>
<P>
Since consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the U.S.
economy, changes in this area are closely watched for signals they
give about the overall economy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economy grew at an annual rate of 5.8 percent in the
first three months of this year, the fastest clip in nearly a
decade, according to a U.S. government report released late last
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
