<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Sees No Threat from Left Victory in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
said today he did not see the victory of the French left in
Sunday's general election as a threat to European Monetary Union
or EU reform.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that France will still hold on to its constructive
European policy even after the government change," Kinkel was
quoted as saying Monday in Luxembourg by the German media.
</P>
<P>
He expected that the new French government would stick to the
timetable of EU reform and the launch of the European single
currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the new prime minister Lionel Jospin had
repeatedly stated his support for the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The EU's target launch for the Euro is January 1, 1999. But
scepticism is growing over whether the deadline can be met as few
members have been able to fulfill the criteria set out in the
Maastricht Treaty governing European Union integration.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was negotiated under the co-leadership of the late
French Socialist President Francois Mitterrand, Kinkel said. "I
have not the slightest doubt about France's loyalty to the
treaty," he added.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Luxembourg for an EU foreign ministerial
meeting, Kinkel told reporters in Bonn that France and Germany
would remain each other's most important partner even after the
government change in Paris.
</P>
<P>
However, the victory of France's left wing parties over the
governing center-right coalition has sent an encouraging signal to
German left-wing parties which are expected to challenge the
center-right ruling coalition of Chancellor Helmut Kohl in next
year's general election.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the German Social Democratic Party Oskar
Lafontaine sent his congratulations to the French Socialists
immediately after the outcome of the election became clear on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
He said, "This is a great success for the future of France and
Europe." It linked people's hopes for a reduction in unemployment
and greater social justice.
</P>
<P>
Germany's left-wing Green Party said, "The outcome of the
elections in France and Britain have shown that the Left in Europe
has become a powerful factor once again." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
