<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Artist and Calligrapher Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Xie Zhiliu, a famous Chinese
artist and master of calligraphy, as well as aesthetic theorist,
passed away here yesterday at the age of 87.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1950's, Xie was in charge of collecting and
appraising calligraphy and artworks at the Shanghai Museum, and
thanks to his great effort, the museum now has a collection of
tens of thousands of artworks.
</P>
<P>
China set up an appraisal group for classical calligraphy and
paintings in 1982, with Xie as its head. Eight years from then
on, Xie Zhiliu and his colleagues visited all museums, libraries
and archaeological sites in China and made a clear order of those
rare works. They also edited the "Catalogue of China's Classical
Calligraphy and Painting".
</P>
<P>
Xie also contributed greatly to research at the Dunhuang
Grottoes in northwest China's Gansu province, where there are many
Buddhist statues, frescoes, and valuable manuscripts dating back to
366 A.D. His "Record of the Dunhuang Grottoes" and "Picture
Catalogue of Dunhuang Arts" are among the most authorative works
on Dunhuang research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern German Wages Still Lag Western Counterparts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Average monthly wages in eastern
Germany rose twice as fast as those in western Germany last year,
but east Germans still earn only about three quarters of their
western counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The monthly income of employees in eastern Germany in 1996
reached 72.5 percent of those in the west, compared with only 70.5
percent in 1995, the German federal statistics office said today.
</P>
<P>
However, with output per worker still half that in western
Germany, the rise in income has been blamed as the main reason for
the lack of competitiveness of the east German economy.
</P>
<P>
The average monthly income of a western German employee
increased from 4,914 German marks (2,900 U.S. dollars) in 1995 to
5,035 marks (2,980 dollars) in 1996, up more than 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In eastern Germany, wages rose from 3,466 marks (2,050 dollars)
to 3,651 marks (2,160 dollars), up over 5.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
