<HEADLINE> Canadians Go to Polls Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Canadian voters head to polls today
to decide who will lead them into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
The general election comes after a five-week campaign, during
which Canadians showed little enthusiasm for the political
debates, handshakes and promises.
</P>
<P>
Though the nation's unemployment problem was rated by Canadians
as the number one issue, most of the campaign has been about
national unity.
</P>
<P>
The political debates are mostly about what strategy should be
adopted to deal with separatists and who should lead the
federalists into the next referendum.
</P>
<P>
There are about 19 million registered voters in Canada, many of
whom have indicated that they would not come out to vote.
</P>
<P>
Despite all this, the ruling Liberal Party is widely expected
to win in the 301-seat parliament and form a majority government.
</P>
<P>
In the last general election, the Liberals won 177 seats out of
a total of 295.
</P>
<P>
The separatist Bloc Quebecois won 54 seats and became the
official opposition in the parliament. The Reform Party got 52
seats, the New Democratic Party nine and the Progressive
Conservative two.
</P>
<P>
This time, the right-wing Reform Party appears to have
fortified its position and is expected to displace the Bloc
Quebecois as the official opposition, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
The polls open at 9:30 a.m. (local time) and close at 9:30
p.m. The final results of the election aren't expected to come out
until about 11 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
