<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Pushes Scientific Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing, speaking
at a ceremony for the establishment of the Higher Education
Research Center of Qinghua University today, said that China can
only remain competitive in the world economy and science and
technology by maintaining a high level of scientific research.
</P>
<P>
Basic research, which is a major source of new ideas, can have
a revolutionary impact on new techniques with its breakthroughs,
and qualified people and research results are important signs of
the progress of a civilization and comprehensive national
strength, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government should be aware of the enormous
impact of basic research on economic and social development and
should give more support for basic research.
</P>
<P>
He said that the initiative of young scientists and middle-aged
and senior scientists should be aroused fully and that research
centers should be improved to create better conditions and a
better academic environment.
</P>
<P>
Also, international exchanges and cooperation should be
increased to provide more opportunities for high-level personnel
in an international scientific environment.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the new research center is basic scientific
research, and "Cultivating creative scientific personnel for the
21st Century and the world, and increasing international academic
exchanges and co-operation", said Wang Dazhong, president of
Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Prominent physicist and Nobel Prize winner Prof. Chen Ning Yang
from the United States and Physicist Nie Huatong serve as honorary
director and director of the center, Wang said.
</P>
