<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Plans to Improve Technology in Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has a plan
to improve the skill and technology used in the country's vast and
often poverty-stricken rural areas, officials here said today.
</P>
<P>
The country's ninth development plan, to be introduced later
this year, has the objective of gradually encouraging and
developing the existing technologies in rural areas, according to
officials of the Ministry of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
New achievements in science and technology will be extended to
the rural people to improve the productivity of the agricultural
sector, they told a national seminar on technology development
held here today.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand, while opening the
seminar, said that scientific research in Nepal must define its
objectives in terms of usefulness to common people under the
economic principles of benefit and cost.
</P>
<P>
Chand, who is also minister of science and technology, called
on local scientists and researchers to come up with
recommendations that could serve as guidelines to define the
country's goals and strategies in the science and technology
sector.
</P>
<P>
Official estimates show that Nepal currently spends only 0.1
percent of gross domestic product (GDP) on science and technology,
far less than the average of nearly 1 percent among developing
countries in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
