<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study to Trace Cargo Movements Between Hong Kong and Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will carry out a study
to trace the fast growing cargo movements between this port city
and ports in the Pearl River Delta in southern China.
</P>
<P>
Focusing on river trade cargo handling activities in 1997, the
study would serve as the basis for future planning of port
facilities in Hong Kong, according to an official of the Hong Kong
Port Development Board (PDB).
</P>
<P>
The PDB earmarked more than two million HK dollars (256,000
U.S. dollars) for the study, which will be undertaken by Survey
Research Hongkong Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Richard Yuen, secretary of the Port Development Board, said
today: "Hong Kong is experiencing a rapid growth in river trade,
and the Pearl river is a natural highway between Hong Kong and
many manufacturing centers in southern China."
</P>
<P>
He noted that river trade throughput grew by some 27 percent to
1.7 million twenty-foot equivalent units (TEUs) last year. The
figure is forecast to rise to 2.4 million TEUs by 1998 and to 3.7
million by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, regular monitoring of river cargo performance was
essential to devising development plans for port facilities, said
Yuen. The study is expected to be completed in mid-1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
