<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Pledges Continued Support for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Kofi Annan, U.N.Secretary General,
today pledged continued U.N.support for African countries, saying
joint efforts should be intensified for peace and development in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Annan, addressing the opening session of the 33rd summit of
African countries here, said that the U.N. will continue its
long-standing efforts to help Africa create an enabling
environment for economic growth and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to assist your efforts to devise new
investment strategies and trade barriers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that following political independence and the end
of apartheid, Africa is experiencing "the third wave".
</P>
<P>
"Let us make this third wave one of lasting peace on
democracy, human rights, and sustainable development," Annan
said.
</P>
<P>
He put forward the following proposals to "unleash Africa's
third wave in full force":
</P>
<P>
-- Embrace the primacy of democratic rule, the inviolability
of human rights, and the imperatives of sustainable development;
</P>
<P>
-- Governmental authority be based on the will of the people;
</P>
<P>
-- Restore the constitutional order in countries where
"democracy has been usurped"; and
</P>
<P>
-- Put an end to conflicts which have disfigured the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
Annan condemned coups against elected governments, and the
illegal seizure of power by military cliques. He urged
neighboring states, regional groupings, and the international
community to "ostracize and isolate putschists."
</P>
<P>
"Verbal condemnation, though necessary and desirable, is not
sufficient," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us work together, and with the United Nations to develop
good governance and respect for the rule of law," he said. "When
we succeed, Africa will have taken a great step forward."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
