<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Opposes Regional Economic Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim
Khaddam said today that Syria is opposed to the convocation of the
fourth Middle East and North African (MENA) Economic Summit when
Israel is still obstructing the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"It is meaningless to hold such a meeting when the Israeli
policy is posing serious obstacles to the peace process," said Syrian
after a meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam and Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara arrived for a
few-hour visit here this morning, carrying a message from
President Hafez Al-Assad to Mubarak, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The annual MENA conference, to be held this year in Doha,
Qatar, has been regarded as a direct spin-off of the progress in
the Mideast peace process since the early 1990s and a way to
expand regional economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Syria, an important partner in the Mideast peace process, began
negotiations with Israel in 1991. But the sporadic talks broke off
last February after a spate of suicide bomb attacks in Israel
blamed on Palestinian extremists.
</P>
<P>
The Arab-Israeli ties have further deteriorated since the
Israeli Likud assumed power last June, culminating in a
two-month-old crisis over a new Jewish settlement Israel began to
build in March in disputed Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian Vice President said that regarding the recent
developments in the region, Arab countries should pool their
efforts in building an Arab community that is open to
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Egypt will work for the establishment of the common
Arab market, Khaddam added.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam said he also discussed with Mubarak the Turkish
incursion into northern Iraq, Israeli-Turkish military agreement
and the Israeli "recalcitrant stances" in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Egypt have been in close coordination in restarting
the Israeli-Syrian peace talks that have been frozen for over one
year.
</P>
<P>
Syria refused to return to the negotiating table with the
Israeli government unless it first agrees to pull out of the Golan
Heights, captured by the Jewish state in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu rejects the demand,
saying that the strategic plateau is vital to Israel. But his
predecessors, Labor Party leaders reportedly verbally accepted an
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan in return for normalized ties
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria favors a pan-Arab summit to make resolute decisions to
confront the Israeli settlement practice, which has led to the
stalemate in the Israeli-Palestinian peace track since two months
ago, but Egypt said such a move is premature.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first country to make peace with the Jewish state,
has been one of the key mediators in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Anti-Dumping Measures on Norwegian Salmon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
approved a package of measures to counteract the dumping of
Norwegian salmon on the European market and protect salmon
producers of European Union (EU) countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the measures negotiated and agreed with Norway, Norwegian
salmon exporters will respect a minimum price of 3.25 ECUs (some
4.2 U.S. dollars) per kilogram. If the price falls below that
level, their salmon exports into the EU will automatically incur
import duties.
</P>
<P>
The deal follows an investigation which found that Norwegian
salmon was being dumped onto the EU market between 1995 and 1996,
harming the interests of salmon farmers of several EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The measures also included stand-by dumping duties, export
volume limits, an increased Norwegian export tax and tight
surveillance procedures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
