<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Opens With Maintenance of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The 33rd ordinary conference of
heads of state and government of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) opened here today with the topic of maintenance of
peace and economic development stressed.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert G. Mugabe in his official address
stressed that economic development needs maintenance of peace.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, "Economic questions have now clearly come to the
fore. To solve them, however, we need a correct political
environment on the continent. Perhaps the most urgent issue
facing Africa today is the vital question of peace in a number of
our countries, for peace is such a fundamental pre-condition for
the enjoyment of all other rights by our citizens."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that without peace "every other aspiration is
stunted, circumvented, curtailed and even denied. It is
therefore, proper and indeed imperative that both our
organization and individual countries give top priority to the
establishment of maintenance of peace through our mechanism for
the resolution of conflicts".
</P>
<P>
Referring to economy in the continent, Mugabe said, "A
fundamental need in Africa is to ensure sustained economic growth
and development in order to adequately cater for the needs of our
burgeoning population and enhance the quality of life of our
people."
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, Mugabe said, "Our aim, as goverrnments, is
to ensure that there is peace and tranquility in our countries."
</P>
<P>
About 30 heads of state and government attended today's
session of the OAU Summit. Other leaders of OAU member states are
represented by their foreign ministers or other high ranking
officials.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan and Officials of
other UN bodies, as well as the diplomatic corps here were
invited to attend the session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
