<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Calls for Good Use of Research Findings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin said today
that how to turn research findings into practical productive
forces is a major task for China in its effort to create a
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remark in a meeting with 70 Chinese and overseas
scientists who are in Beijing for the inaugural ceremony of the
Higher Research Center of Qinghua University and a symposium on
the Prospects of Basic Science for the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China scored considerable achievements in
scientific and technologic development during the period of a
planned economy, but there were places where the findings and
their use diverged.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, Chinese enterprises lack new products that meet
the market demand in China, and research findings of some
institutions have not been put to good use, he said, noting: "If
research findings are not turned promptly into practical
productive forces, they will not be helpful to the further
development of science and technology."
</P>
<P>
In congratulating the university on the establishment of its
research center, Jiang said that, since the beginning of the 20th
century, great progress has been made in science and technology in
the world, thus exerting an enormous impact on the social
development of mankind.
</P>
<P>
The thesis of the late leader Deng Xiaoping that science and
technology are primary productive forces has been proven
entirely correct, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
But turning researching findings into practical productive
forces does not mean neglecting research into basic sciences, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The leader said, "I have stated several times that as regards
basic research, we should score achievements in some areas and
don't have to so in some other areas. Developed countries ought to
spend more manpower and materials in this regard."
</P>
<P>
Chen Ning Yang, the Chinese American scientist who won the 1957
Nobel prize in physics, speaking on behalf of all scientists
present, said, "We are delighted to notice that the Chinese
government has always paid close attention to and supported
research into basic sciences."
</P>
<P>
International competition in the future will lie primarily in
the area of science and technology, he said, noting that to
improve competitiveness in science and technology, it is
imperative to develop applied sciences, and attach great
importance to research into basic sciences as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
