<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Prime Minister Calls for Innovation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong said today that the government wants to bring about a mindset
change among Singaporeans by encouraging a spirit of innovation
and learning.
</P>
<P>
"We must get away from the idea that it is only the people at
the top who should be thinking, and the job of everyone else is to
do as told. Instead we want to bring about a spirit of innovation,
of learning by doing," he said at the opening of the Seventh
International Conference on Thinking.
</P>
<P>
He said Singapore's vision for meeting future challenges is
encapsulated in four words: Thinking Schools, Learning Nation,
which, he explained, is a vision for a total learning environment,
including students, teachers, parents, workers, companies,
community, organizations and government.
</P>
<P>
Thinking Schools, Learning Nation is a formula that will enable
Singapore to compete and stay ahead, the prime minister said,
adding that the concept of thinking schools is central to this
vision.
</P>
<P>
Schools must develop future generations of thinking and
committed citizens, capable of making good decisions to keep
Singapore vibrant and successful in future, Goh urged.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education is undertaking a fundamental review
of its curriculum and assessment system to see how the creative
thinking and learning skills required for the future can be better
developed.
</P>
<P>
"What is critical however is that we fire in our students a
passion for learning, instead of studying for the sake of getting
good grades in their examinations," he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
