<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges for Joint Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordan' Prime Minister Abdul-Salam
Majali today urged all parties in the Mideast peace process to
jointly work toward realizing regional and international peace.
</P>
<P>
Meeting an Israeli delegation, the prime minister said peace is
the ordinary state of human life and war should disappear forever.
</P>
<P>
He said peace is the common language for all the three great
religions in Arab East Jerusalem: Muslim, Christianity and
Judaism.
</P>
<P>
Peace can not be brought about as a result of building a
settlement here or there, but a comprehensive state, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Jordan hopes that the Israeli public will be more active in
pressing ahead for the goal of making peace, said Majali, who
signed a peace treaty with the Israelis in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Majali's meeting with the Israeli delegation came after the
U.S. and Egypt failed to reactiviate the Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks last month and the hardline Israeli government declared to
continue building Jewish settlements in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is believed to be the birthplaces of all the three
religions and the Palestinians want it as the capital of their
future state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
