<HEADLINE> Kenya Ready to Resume Diplomatic Relations with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is waiting for a formal
request from Kigali to reopen the Rwandan embassy here,
the East African today quoted a source of Kenyan Foreign
Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Once the request is received, the rest will be a formality,"
the Kenyan official pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that at a regional summit on Burundi held in
Arusha last April, Kenya abandoned her hardline position against
the Tutsi military junta in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kenyan Foreign Ministry, the paper said, Kenya is
now even willing to support Rwanda's application for East African
Co-operation membership.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to look at their application favourably," an
official of Kenya's Foreign Ministry was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kenya and Rwanda were broken up in June last
year when the Kenyan government ordered the Rwandan embassy in
Nairobi to close.
</P>
<P>
Hostility between the two countries took root in 1994
following the demise of the regime of the late President Juvenal
Habyarimana and the coming to power of the Rwandan Patriotic
Front.
</P>
<P>
The new Rwandan authorities were bitter about the presence in
Kenya of senior Hutu leaders alleged to have mastermined or been
involved in the 1994 genocide against Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
The worsening relations had culminated in the expulsion of two
successive Rwandan Charges d'Affaires in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted analysts as saying that Kenya's change of
position on Rwanda had come about as a result of recent
geopolitical shifts in the Great Lakes region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
