<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Thailand to Hold Border Committee Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Thailand will
hold their 39th General Border Committee (GBC) meeting here
beginning June 5.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, who is also defense
minister, will head a 30-member delegation to the three-day
meeting, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported
today.
</P>
<P>
He will be accompanied by Deputy Army Chief-of-Staff Lt. Gen.
Chokechai Hongthong and Director-General of the Police Department
Gen. Pracha Promnok.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will be represented by Defense Minister Syed Hamid
Albar who will lead a 25-member delegation which includes Armed
Forces Chief Gen. Ismail Omar, Chief of Staff Gen. Nawi Alias and
Deputy Inspector-General of Police Norian Mai, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from the two sides will meet over the next two
days to lay the groundwork for the meeting which is expected to
cover several issues related to their common border and review
past security arrangements, officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The officials said the meeting is expected to focus on
cross-border movement of people and prevention of smuggling
activities along the 647-kilometer-long border shared by the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
An agreement is expected to be endorsed on the last day of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Thailand agreed to jointly develop border areas
that are difficult to demarcate and they signed an agreement on
March 8 for the Golok River Mouth Improvement Project that would
also help determine a more precise boundary demarcation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also conducted joint naval, air and army
exercises annually under the auspices of the GBC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
