<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paper Says Iranian Leader Intervenes Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei
intervened in Sunday's Parliament election by lobbying for his
close aide Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri for the post of speaker, the
Persian daily Jomhuri Islami reported today.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted Abdollah Nouri, Nateq-Nouri's rival for the
post of Parliament speaker, as saying that Khamenei had asked
him to leave the race on favor of Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
"I withdrew my candidacy after I heard the views of His
Eminence Supreme Leader that Mr. Nateq-Nouri must continue to
stay as Parliament speaker," Abdollah Nouri said.
</P>
<P>
A source close to Abdollah Nouri told Xinhua that Nouri came
under the pressure of Khamenei's office to leave the race for
speaker's seat after Nateq-Nouri lost to Mohammad Khatami by a
wide 13-million-vote margin in Iran's 7th presidential election
on May 23.
</P>
<P>
"First Mr. Abdollah Nouri was approached and pressured by the
leader's office. Then he went and met with the leader."
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the leader and Abdollah Nouri was
reported by other dailies as well. But the leftist opposition
daily Salam in today's report on the meeting left two paragraphs
blank.
</P>
<P>
This kind of move is rare in the history of printing media in
the country and could be interpreted as a strong protest against
the news censorship by the Islamic regime.
</P>
<P>
Reached by phone, the daily declined to comment on the blank
paragraph spaces that appeared in its interview with Abdollah
Nouri.
</P>
<P>
On May 22, a day before presidential elections, Iranian police
raided the printing house of Salam and closed the printing
house. The printing house was later opened on the same day but
it led to the disruption of the distribution of the popular
daily which supported Khatami's challenge to Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Unchallenged in his bid for re-election as parliament
speaker, Nateq-Nouri Sunday gained 211 out of 243 votes in
the Parliament, which will make him the speaker for another
year.
</P>
<P>
Most political analysts here believe that President-elect
Mohammad Khatami will face a tough time ahead since the
conservatives backed by Khamenei dominate the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Khatami will have to introduce the members of his cabinet to
obtain the Parliament vote of confidence for each minister. The
winning faction in the Parliament will have the last word in
determining the nature of Khatami's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Abdollah Nouri was the candidate of the Majma'e Hizbollah
(Party of God Association), a coalition of the leftists and
liberals who support the liberal policies of the outgoing
President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The Party of God Association, a supporter of Khatami, is
expected to fully back Khatami against the rightists when he
introduces his cabinet to the Parliament early August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
