<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Hospital Train in China to Be Launched on July 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The first hospital train in
China, Lifetime Express, will depart from Hong Kong on July 1 and
travel through the Chinese inland areas, providing free medical
services to the poverty-stricken and handicapped living in poor
and remote areas.
</P>
<P>
The idea of operating the express, which is similar to a
program in India, was inspired by a group of Hong Kong people who
want to help the handicapped, the sick and the poor.
</P>
<P>
The project is proceeding under the leadership of the Chinese
Ministry of Health in conjunction with the Ministry of Railways
and the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office under the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Executive Committee of the express, Ms Nellie
Fong, said, "Comprising three carriages, the Lifeline Express is
scheduled to visit five selected areas in China each year and
provide three types of services, including corrective treatment of
cataracts and poliomyelitis as well as education on primary health
care and hygiene."
</P>
<P>
The train will emphasize cataract treatment during its first
year of operation, she said, adding Fengyang in east China's Anhui
Province has been chosen as the train's first stop.
</P>
<P>
Representing seven Hong Kong medical practitioners
participating in the program, Chairman of the Hong Kong Medical
Association Dr. Lee Kin-hung said, "According to rough estimates,
there are over 3 million people in the inland areas who suffer
from cataracts. It is difficult for them to take care of their
daily needs."
</P>
<P>
Transplant of artificial lenses to cataract patients will
improve their sight up to 70 percent of normal vision, he said.
</P>
<P>
The doctors from Hong Kong will work together with their
counterparts in the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
There will be a permanent staff of 16 from the Ministry of
Health on the express to take care of the day-to-day operations of
the train. Based on the selection of stops, the ministry will also
allocate medical staff from the nearby cities to assist in the
operation of the train.
</P>
<P>
In order to facilitate the effective operation of the train,
the Ministry of Health will join hands with the Ministry of
Railways and provincial and municipal governments in determining
the list of places where the express will visit.
</P>
<P>
The train will stay for about 30 to 40 days in each place.
Publicity and patient registration will start ten days before the
arrival of the train.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
