<HEADLINE> Malaysian Acting PM Praises ASEAN Decision to Admit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Acting prime
minister Anwar Ibrahim said today the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) had made a correct decision in admitting
Myanmar into the regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is free to express its views but I think
ASEAN has made a correct decision," he told reporters in the
Parliament House when asked to comment on a statement by a U.S
State Department spokesman expressing regrets over ASEAN's
decision.
</P>
<P>
"We believe in constructive engagement and we believe in
dialogues among ASEAN countries," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was time that ASEAN brings neighboring countries
together as a cohesive force. "I think that is the wisdom and we
have proven this to work."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's foreign ministers made a unanimous decision at their
special meeting here on May 31 that Myanmar, along with Cambodia
and Laos will be formally admitted into the regional grouping in
July this year during the ASEAN Ministerial meeting here.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN at present groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore,
the Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
