<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Handover Celebration at Full Steam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- With the approaching of the Hong
Kong's return to China, Hong Kong people have begun to express
their joy and happy feelings in a wide variety of celebration
activities.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that from June 1 to the end of July,
more than 200 mass celebrating activities will be staged by
various local organizations and social groups.
</P>
<P>
These activities vary in style and content, involving sports
events, theatrical performances, exhibitions, banquets, bus and
ship tours, public carnivals, flying and film shows.
</P>
<P>
Sunday saw the unveiling of several major events all at once.
They included a month-long marathon-style relay race from Hong
Kong to Beijing, an international basketball tournament, a grand
prayer meeting attended by thousands of Christians and a
997-meter-long scroll painting by young people depicting the past,
present and future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The celebration sentiment is expected to peak on the nights of
June 30 and July 1, when several mass activities are staged.
</P>
<P>
The largest event, the Hong Kong 97 Spectacular scheduled for
July 1, is a light and sound show which includes an illuminated
flotilla, music, water fountains, special effects, lights, lasers
and fireworks display on Victoria Harbor.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the event said the show offers the community an
unforgettable spectacle in which the people of Hong Kong can
participate to celebrate and show their confidence in the future.
</P>
<P>
A large TV evening party is planned on June 30 at the Cultural
Center, which will draw over 400 artists from the inland areas and
more than 600 noted figures from local artistic and performing
circles. The party will be broadcast live worldwide by local TV
stations.
</P>
<P>
A carnival in Victoria Park organized by the Hong Kong Women's
Association for Celebrating Hong Kong's Return to China will start
at 10 a.m. on June 30 and last until the morning of July 1.
Thousands of families participating in the carnival will be able
to watch the grand handover ceremony through large TV screens
mounted on the site.
</P>
<P>
Industries and districts have all set up their respective
committees for organizing celebration activities, the latest
addition Sunday being the Cheung Chau Association for Celebrating
Hong Kong's Return to China.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the association said people living on Cheung
Chau Island will have a sleepless night on June 30 with
celebrating banquets, lion dance and sirens. On July 1, people
will take to the streets to join performance tours. A dragon boat
race will also be held on June 8 to mark the handover.
</P>
<P>
On June 22, nine dragons, 100 lions and over 60 performing
teams will be dancing through the streets of Yuen Long in the New
Territories, while on the night of June 28 a 3.5-kilometer-long
dragon delineated with neon lights will show its prowess along the
Nathan Road in Kowloon.
</P>
<P>
Most of these activities have been self-sponsored and
self-funded. Hong Kong people are generous in handing out money to
make the whole thing possible and also show their excitement at
the historic event by active participation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
