<HEADLINE> Fighting Intense in Freetown With No Clear Winner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Intense fighting is still going
on in Sierra Leone's capital Freetown between Nigeria-led west
African intervening troops and the coup soldiers allied with
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian peacekeeping troops took control of the
international airport at Lungi, north of the capital earlier
today while the rebels and coup soldiers outnumbered the
peacekeepers outside a Freetown hotel.
</P>
<P>
According to a commander of the ECOMOG, west Africa's
peacekeeping forces, Nigerian troops already gained full control
of the airport to protect it from rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
"We took it this morning. There was a fighting with the
Sierra Leonean forces but it didn't last long at all," said the
officer.
</P>
<P>
The international airport would immediately be put into use to
bring in rapid reinforcements from other west African countries
including Nigeria, Ghana and Guinea.
</P>
<P>
However, despite earlier reports that an estimated 3,000
ECOMOG soldiers surrounded the 1,800 rebels allied with coup
soldiers, the coup soldiers and rebels gained an upper hand in
some districts of the capital.
</P>
<P>
They massed around a Freetown hotel guarded by Nigerian troops
after ECOMOG launched a bombardment and ground attack against the
coup leaders.
</P>
<P>
"The Nigerians are outnumbered and outgunned, there is no sign
or prospect of reinforcement. The rebels are massing closer and
closer to the hotel," said a Nigerian peacekeeping officer at the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
The hotel holds a few foreign journalists and about 1,000 west
African foreigners who took refuge their after the May 25 coup
when hundreds of foreigners fleeing looting and violence have
been evacuated from Freetown by U.S. marines.
</P>
<P>
The attack came after last night's failure of striking a peace
agreement between British and Nigerian diplomats, and Major Jonny
Koroma, who led his coup soldiers to topple civilian President
Ahmed Kabbah on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Koroma last night announced a new cabinet in a radio broadcast
in Freetown, defying the growing international pressure which
called on coup soldiers to step down and hand back power to
elected President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Foday Sankoh, leader of the rebel Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) which has been fighting a civil war in the tiny west
African country for the last five years, has been appointed
vice-chairman of the new cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
