<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB to Help Address Philippines' Garbage Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is funding a
five-year project to help the Philippines address the worsening
garbage problem across the country.
</P>
<P>
Delfin Ganapin, Undersecretary of the Department of Environment
and Natural Resources, told a press conference here today that the
bank is lending 145 million U.S. dollars to help Manila start the
Solid Waste Ecological Enhancement Project.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, local government units that are willing to
put up environmentally less critical landfill sites will receive
financial support, Ganapin said, adding that some towns and
municipalities have expressed their willingness.
</P>
<P>
The garbage problem has been aggravating across the country
over the past few years. In Metro Manila alone, 6,100 tons of
garbage were generated per day, but there are only two landfills
available and one of them will be closed this month after a number
of years in service.
</P>
<P>
The dire consequences of the serious problem were experienced
when tropical depression Bining caused heavy rains last month,
bringing Metro Manila under water and catching the World Bank's
attention.
</P>
<P>
Ganapin emphasized that landfills are the last measure to
address the worsening problem in the country. He said that garbage
recycling reduces the volume of garbage by 50 percent and
therefore prolongs the life of a landfill.
</P>
<P>
"People should know and practice garbage recycling and garbage
re-use. The residual garbage which can't be recycled shall be
absorbed by the landfills," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
