<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Falls on Rate Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar fell to
levels not seen in almost four months today, driven lower by
speculation that the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) could ease
its official cash rate in the short term.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 75.85 U.S. cents, a level not
seen since February 12, after ending locally last Friday at 76.03
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The RBA holds monthly board meeting Tuesday. An announcement on
monetary policy is generally not expected to follow, with most
analysts predicting any movement would more likely follow the July
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The last rate cut, on May 23, brought the domestic overnight
cash rate from 6.0 percent to 5.5 percent, in line with the
comparable U.S. Federal Reserve rate.
</P>
<P>
Currency traders said the market was jittery ahead of tonight's
offshore session when further selling could emerge.
</P>
<P>
They said demand by local exporters, which had helped support
the Australian dollar over the past week, might not be enough to
support the unit this week.
</P>
<P>
Against the Japanese yen, the Australian dollar ended at 88.17,
down from 88.68 locally last Friday, and the local dollar was at
1.3000 German marks, up from 1.2948.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
