<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An ambitious drinking water
project for Kathmandu is on the top of the new municipal
government's agenda, the capital's major-elect said today.
</P>
<P>
Kashav Sthapit told Xinhua that the city government will try
its best to persuade the central government to invite local and
foreign private investment in the Melamchi water diversion
project.
</P>
<P>
The project would be the only solution to the problem of water
supply shortage in Kathmandu, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sthapit, 38, a youth leader of the ruling Communist Party of
Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML), won a landslide victory
to the mayorship in last week's local elections and is expected to
assume office this week.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government proposed the Melamchi project nearly two
years ago, but so far no investors or foreign donors have shown
keen interest in the 185 million US dollar project, government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
But the newly-elected mayor insisted that the project has its
commercial grounds as there is a huge water supply deficit in the
capital and its surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the government's plans, the Melamchi project,
after its completion, could provide 170 million liters of water
every day to Kathmandu, where daily water demand is around 130
million. At present, only 110 million and 60 million liters are
available in rainy and dry seasons respectively.
</P>
<P>
"What we need now is the government and people's determination
to implement the project," Sthapit said, adding that some local
financial institutions are seriously considering investing in the
project.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, dams, tunnels and a water processing factory
will be built to bring water to the capital from a river about 30
km away.
</P>
<P>
Sthapit, a two-time loser as a candidate for deputy mayor of
Kathmandu in previous elections, said he will reform the city's
administrative structure with a view to carrying out the whole
city planning in an integrated and systematic manner.
</P>
<P>
New measures will also be introduced to mobilize the local
people and the private sector's participation in addressing the
city's headaches of air pollution and bad management of garbage
disposal.
</P>
<P>
Sthapit, one of the youngest mayors in the country, is expected
to face more challenges than he could anticipate now in this
politically sensitive capital city during his term in the next
five years, observers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
