<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sees More Drug Addicts in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A total of 9,888 new cases of
drug addiction and former addicts reverting to the old habit has
been reported in the first three months this year, according to
Malaysia's National Narcotics Agency (NNA).
</P>
<P>
Of the total cases reported, new addicts accounted for 44.7
percent while the rest were those who returned to addiction, NNA
Preventive, Planning and Research Director Abd Rashid Mat Adam was
quoted by the Malaysian national news agency Bernama as saying
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the training for skilled parenting
for drug prevention in Ipoh, some 205 kilometers north of here,
the official described the situation as "serious" and said
preventive efforts should be further intensified to rid the nation
of the menace.
</P>
<P>
He said influence by colleagues was a major contributory factor
in drug addiction, responsible for 28.3 percent of the addicts
while those yearning to know the drug formed 17.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The broken family and the "loose relations" within a family
were also the basic factors behind the driving force to drug
addiction, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
During the three-month period under review, the largest number
of addicts were those below 30 years of age, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 200,000 drug addicts in Malaysia, according
to official figures available.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
