<HEADLINE> Taliban Face Stiff Resistance After Fall of Parwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia face
stiff resistance for the first time since their control of Kabul
after losing Parwan, a strategic province, to the opposition
forces.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today from Kabul, the
Taliban have lost control of northern Parwan province after the
forces loyal to commander Ahmad Shah Masood made a flying start
from Baghlan to Charikar, capital of Parwan province, some 65
kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted anti-Taliban sources as claiming that
Charikar fell to anti-Taliban forces on May 31 followed by their
advance towards Sheegal and Rabat only 50 kilometers from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The sources denied that the Taliban claim of recapturing Jabul
Siraj, a strategic town 77 kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban were ousted from Jabul Siraj and other nearby towns
last Friday. The Taliban's return to Jabul Siraj is impossible
because they themselves had blown up the bridges linking Jabul
Siraj to Charikar while retreating towards Kabul, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban are reported to try to capture a large number of
Shiites from the western parts of the capital.
</P>
<P>
They launched a massive operation in Kabul to arrest as many
Shiites as possible which, they believed, would help secure
release of hundreds of Taliban fighters and leaders captured by
the forces of General Abdul Malik in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A couple of clashes also took place between the Taliban and the
Shiites in Dasht-e-Barchi and Pul-e-Sokhta localities, when the
Taliban arrested more than 100 Shiites from west of Kabul, the
report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
