<HEADLINE> Julius Chan Resumes Prime Ministership Of PNG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Julius Chan today resumed the
prime ministership of Papua New Guinea, a south Pacific nation,
after a two-month-long political crisis.
</P>
<P>
While releasing a 125-page final report in Port Moresby today,
Julius said he had been cleared by a judicial inquiry into a 36
million U.S. dollars mercenaries contract, said the Australian
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Julius, Deputy Prime Minister Chris Haiveta and Defense
Minister Mathias Ijape had been forced to stand down from their
posts in late March following allegations by sacked military
leader Brigadier General Jerry Singirok that the contract to hire
foreign mercenaries was corrupt.
</P>
<P>
Julius told reporters that evidence already given to the
inquiry showed that he had been cleared of any allegations of
corruption surrounding the contract.
</P>
<P>
"It's been completed and all of us have been exonerated, the
deputy prime minister and defense minister would also resume
office," he said.
</P>
<P>
Singirok's allegations sparked military and civil protests in
Port Moresby, eventually forcing the three high officials to stand
aside.
</P>
<P>
Today's announcement by Julius that he would resume the prime
ministership, came barely two weeks before the country's national
elections, due to begin on June 14.  
</P>
