<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Putonghua Becoming Popular Among Macao Civil Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- For 48-year-old Carlos Roldao Lopes,
director of the Macao Posts and Telecommunications Department, it
is now something most urgent to learn Putonghua, or standard
Chinese, in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
The director, who has been in Macao for 23 years, spends one
and half hours in the morning in Putonghua classroom, and then more
than two hours in the evening after he finishes his official
business.
</P>
<P>
"I have decided to remain in Macao after 1999," Lopes told
Xinhua in Putonghua, although not so smoothly, in a recent
interview at the Languages and Translation School under the Macao
Institute of Science and Technology. "Although Putonghua is more
difficult to learn than English, I am confident that I can learn
it well."
</P>
<P>
Like Lopes, thousands of civil servants in Macao are learning
Putonghua eagerly every day. As a matter of fact, the number of
Putonghua learners among civil service has doubled annually in the
school over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
"We now have 155 Chinese classes with 2,325 students," said
Lei Heong Iok, deputy headmaster of the Language and Translation
School, which performs the duty of civil service language
training in the territory. "More than 80 percent of them are
learning Putonghua. They are all very diligent."
</P>
<P>
Students at the school include not only Chinese civil
servants, but also those of Macao-born Portuguese, those coming
from Portugal and even top officials like Lopes and members of the
Legislative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Many of them, Lei said, spend part of their working time in
the morning classroom (from eight o'clock to 9:30) with government
permission. They also study in their spare time.
</P>
<P>
"By overcoming unfavorable factors in time and age (many above
the age of 40), many of them are now able to communicate in
simple Putonghua after learning for 70 hours," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government started Chinese training among civil servants
in 1987, in an effort to implement the policy of using Chinese as
an official language. Established in 1991, the Language and
Translation School is the largest Chinese training center for
civil servants.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1993, there were about 20 to 30 Chinese
classes in each school year, with students numbering 300 to
500. After 1993, the number doubled each year to more than 1,000
people during the 1995-1996 period, and to 2,325 during the
1996-1997 period.
</P>
<P>
So far, an estimated 10,000 out of the 17,000 or so civil
servants have received Chinese language training.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 factor plays a most significant role in the civil
servants' enthusiasm in learning Putonghua, although some said
they are interested in the Chinese language.
</P>
<P>
"I need to speak Putonghua in my work," said Leng Wun Teng, a
clerk with the Government Tourism Office. "But I think I should be
able to speak Putonghua as China is to resume the exercise of
its sovereignty (over Macao) in two and half years."
</P>
<P>
Maria Gomes Costa, headmaster of the Languages and Translation
School, said that her school has compiled different textbooks and
opened different classes for different students.
</P>
<P>
"The government has made great efforts in training bilingual
professionals," she said, "The training program includes both
Chinese and Portuguese, in accordance with the basic law of
Macao." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian MPs Optimistic About Future of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An Australian parliamentary
committee expressed here today their optimism about the future of
Hong Kong after its handover to China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the parliament, the Joint Standing Committee on
Foreign Affairs, Defense and Trade said its "optimism is
encouraged by the robust state of Hong Kong's economy, the
autonomous representation of Hong Kong on a number of
international economic bodies," such as the World Trade
Organization (WTO), and its maintenance of a separate currency,
its own stock exchange and its status as a separate customs
territory.
</P>
<P>
In a tabling statement today to the House of Representatives,
Ian Sinclair, chairman of the committee, said, "Hong Kong has a
sophisticated common law system, an independent judiciary, a
vigorous Chinese and English language media and an impartial and
apparently honest public service and police force."
</P>
<P>
"Optimism about the future of Hong Kong rests, we were told, on
the rational and pragmatic nature of the Chinese government and
its recognition of the value of Hong Kong to China," the chairman
said.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair, who went to Hong Kong with his colleagues on a
fact-finding trip earlier this year, said optimism about Hong
Kong's future also rests on the agreement of the Chinese to "a
novel treaty that guarantees 'one country, two systems' and 'Hong
Kong people governing Hong Kong'."
</P>
<P>
He said Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji reiterated those
promises last week during a visit to Australia.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier said: "China would unswervingly implement the
principle of 'one country, two systems' and we have the ability
and the confidence to ensure long-term stability and prosperity of
Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"We think business will flourish rather than reverse," Sinclair
said later at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the "fairly late" changes made by Hong Kong
Governor Christopher Patten, MP C Hollis told journalists that he
thinks Britain showed "a certain amount of hypocrisy" in making
the changes only four years ago.
</P>
<P>
"And of course that was after the Sino-British agreement," said
Hollis, who also visited Hong Kong in January.
</P>
<P>
"I sensed in Hong Kong a very strong feeling in a lot of
sections of the community toward China ... a feeling in Chinese
that 'we are going back to China'," Hollis said.
</P>
<P>
The 217-page report is a product of an inquiry by the
committee, whose six members visited Hong Kong between January 19
and 25, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The six MPs were able to hold "extensive" discussions with
senior government officials, politicians from all political
parties, the legal fraternity, religious leaders, business people
and representatives from a variety of non-governmental
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
