<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Sewage Treatment Works Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Stonecutters Island sewage
treatment works, one of the largest of its kind in the world,
opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The 2.1 billion-HK-dollar plant is capable of treating 1.7
million cubic meters of sewage a day to serve a population of
about 3.5 million by the year 2021.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, John Collier, director of
Drainage Services, said the treatment works is a key component of
the strategic sewage disposal scheme, a long-term solution to the
treatment and disposal of the sewage which presently flows into
the Victoria Harbor.
</P>
<P>
"The plant provides treatment for domestic and industrial waste
from across the main urban area of Kowloon and Northeast Hong Kong
Island," he added.
</P>
<P>
The treatment works adopts a chemically enhanced primary
sedimentation process where ferric chloride and polymer chemicals
are added to increase the treatment efficiency of the
sedimentation tanks.
</P>
<P>
That will remove at least 70 percent of the suspended solid
pollution and 35 percent of the biological oxygen demand of the
waste water.
</P>
<P>
According to Collier, the operational control of the entire
system is by a sophisticated computerized Distributed Control and
Data Acquisition System.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
