<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian President on Hung Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indian President S.D. Sharma said
today that it needed to have conventions to deal with hung
parliament phenomenon in the country.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating a two-day conference of governors here, the
president said that there was need to build healthy conventions
that facilitate the task of the constitutional head and the
working of the constitution in different situations.
</P>
<P>
In the past couple of years, India has seen hung parliament or
assemblies both in the center and states with no single party
getting a simple majority in the legislatures.
</P>
<P>
Sharma posed several questions to the participants that might
crop up if no political party secures a clear majority in the
parliamentary or assembly polls and expressed the hope that the
conference would serve as reference material of permanent value
for future state heads.
</P>
<P>
Apart from governors, the conference is being attended by
leaders of several political parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sharma stressed the importance to safeguard and ensure smooth
working of the constitution with the help of institutions and
systems which can "efficiently and confidently deal with the
phenomenon of hung legislatures".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
