<HEADLINE> W. African Troops Attack S. Leone Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Ground fighting occurred around
the military headquarters in Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone
today after warships of the west African peacekeeping forces, led
by Nigeria, started bombing the coup makers at dawn.
</P>
<P>
Coup soldiers exchanged fire with Nigerian troops protecting a
hotel near the military headquarters in which about 1,000 west
African foreigners are holed up.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners took refuge in the basement of the hotel which
was shattered by the gunfire. Some Nigerian soldiers were wounded
outside the hotel.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the coup leaders speaking on state radio urged
people to come out and protest against the Nigerian intervention.
Meanwhile, a spokesman for ECOMOG, the west African peacekeeping
forces, said the ECOMOG attack against the coup leaders had started.
</P>
<P>
The coup leaders are currently based in the camps of the
military headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The attack came after last night's failure of striking a peace
agreement between British and Nigerian diplomats, and Major Jonny
Koroma, who led his coup soldiers to topple civilian President
Ahmed Kabbah on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Major Koroma last night announced a new cabinet of Sierra
Leone in a radio broadcast in Freetown, defying the growing
international pressure which called on him to step down and
hand back power to elected President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Corporal Foday Sankoh, leader of the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) which has been fighting a civil
war in the tiny west African country for the last five years, has
been appointed vice-chairman of the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, who is now in Nigeria's capital Abuja under a house
arrest by the Nigerian government, reportedly ordered his rebels
to join the new regime. Three other RUF rebels are also in the
20-member cabinet list.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that an estimated 3,000 ECOMOG soldiers
in Freetown surrounded the 1,800 rebel troops, including RUF
fighters. With the troops build up, ECOMOG has brought several
tanks, artillieries and personnel carriers into Freetown, to make
preparations for a possible attack pending any failure of the
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
