<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman, Iran to Jointly Develop Oilfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Oman and Iran have agreed to
draw up a joint development plan for Buka-Hengam oilfield which
is jointly owned by the two countries, local newspaper Khaleej
Time reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was announced Sunday following a meeting in
Muscatt, the capital of Oman, between Oman's undersecretary for
Oil Salem Shaaban and his Iranian counterpart Mohammed Hadi
Najad Hussainian, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Shaaban told the newspaper that the two sides agreed to set up
basis for developing the oilfield, which stretches over the
territorial waters of the two countries near the strategic Hormuz
Strait at the entrance of the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
A joint team will discuss the financial and legal aspects of
the development plan within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a tangible progress has been made in
the plan to develop the oilfield, the Omani official said.
</P>
<P>
The field is economically viable and Oman has tested two wells
in its side of the field, while Iran also drilled a well, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Iran said earlier that the field would be put to international
tender. Some European and Australian companies have already shown
interest.
</P>
<P>
Iran said it owns about 80 percent of the field, with the rest
owned by Oman.
</P>
<P>
Iran estimates that the field's reserves include 523 cubic
meters of natural gas and 120 million barrels of crude
oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
