<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 06:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proliferation-Proof Nuclear Reactor Designed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli scientist has
invented a technology to build a new kind of nuclear reactor
which will greatly reduce the global threat of nuclear terrorism
and cost of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post reported today that Alvin Radkowsky, a
nuclear scientist in the Hebrew University, invented the
technology that uses thorium instead of uranium for much of the
fuel in the core of nuclear reactors,
</P>
<P>
This technology does not produce any by-products that could
possibly be used for making weapons, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
At present, all the approximately 400 commercial light-water
reactors in the world discharge over 70 tonnes of plutonium
annually. And only four kilograms of plutonium is enough to make a
nuclear bomb.
</P>
<P>
The new invention is known as the non-proliferative
light-water thorium reactor, or the Radkowsky Thorium Reactor
(RTR). Thorium is much more plentiful and cheaper than uranium,
but until now no practical method was found to exploit its
potential in nuclear energy production.
</P>
<P>
Radkowsky, a former chief scientist of the United States Naval
Nuclear Propulsion Program for 24 years who immigrated to Israel
in 1972, noted that another advantage of the RTR is a major
reduction in nuclear waste, not only in quantity and toxicity, but
also in radioactivity and heat emission. Nuclear-power countries
are facing serious problems in storing nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
The RTR could reduce nuclear power costs by 20 percent to 30
percent, partly due to the savings in uranium, Radkowsky
said. It is exactly the same size as existing standard uranium
cores, so it can easily be substituted.
</P>
<P>
The United States Patent Office has granted a patent to
Radkowsky, and the Japanese and Russian governments have already
approved his invention.
</P>
<P>
A cooperation agreement was recently signed with the Nuclear
Fuel Industries of Japan, and a full-scale prototype RTR is now
being built at the Kurchatov Institute in Moscow with
U.S. government funding and is expected to be ready by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Radkowsky presented information about the reactor
to the International Atomic Energy Agency in Vienna, which is
now considering it for approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
