<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Change 2-day Weekly Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is to
change its just-announced two-day weekly holiday because of
pressure from the opposition party, government employees and the
business community.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the government declared Friday and Saturday as
weekly holidays, instead of only Friday, to "increase efficiency
and productivity, save expenditure on account of fuel, energy and
check environment pollution" in work places.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leader and former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia has
accused the government of making the nation handicapped by
announcing a two-day weekly holiday as "part of evil designs by
local and foreign powers".
</P>
<P>
"It has announced two days holiday instead of one day's merely
to make a just-awakened nation somnolent in the present
competitive world," she alleged.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's two leading trade bodies also urged the government
to review its decision of two-day holiday and declare Sunday as
the weekly holiday.
</P>
<P>
The Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce and Industry (MCCI) in a
statement on Sunday said Sunday should be weekly holiday and
Saturday as half day.
</P>
<P>
President of the Dhaka Chamber of Commerce and Industry ASM
Quasem also shared the similar view, "the government's abrupt
decision on weekly holiday without any discussion with the
business community has come as a disappointment to us," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hundreds of government employees Sunday staged a
demonstration inside the Bangladesh Secretariat, demanding the
rescinding of two-day weekly holiday.
</P>
<P>
The employees and junior officials, ignoring official ban on
holding rally inside this compound of different ministries, took
out a series of group processions and organized a big rally.
</P>
<P>
They demanded an immediate withdrawal of the newly-introduced
restriction on rallies and immediate reversion to the previous
office time-table. According to the new time-table, they are to
work from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., instead of from 8 a.m. to 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Friday was made the weekly holiday from Sunday in early 1980s
in this predominately Moslem country by the then president Hussain
Muhammad Ershad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
