<HEADLINE> Philippine House Speaker Denies Rumors to Oust Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine House Speaker Jose de
Venecia today laughed off rumors on an impending plan to unseat
him, labeling the rumors as only "black propaganda and intrigue".
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, reports from an unnamed source from the ruling
Lakas party said a coup in the lower Chamber has been brewing and
would push through when the Congress is on recess beginning this
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the plot has got the backing of key officials
in the Presidential Palace and that House Majority Leader Rodolfo
Albano had been groomed by the Palace to replace de Venecia.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia said the rumors were meant to destabilize the House.
In the meantime, he expressed confidence that he still has the
support of at least 169 congressmen out of the 250 lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
The speaker said some people fabricated these rumors maybe
because his "performance and achievement ratings were quite
improving. But he did not explain this matter further.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia is among the few people wanting to be anointed by
President Fidel Ramos in the 1998 elections. He faces challenges
from main rivals including Defense Secretary Renato de Villa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
