<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Towns Booming in Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Small towns in east China's
Zhejiang Province have developed rapidly in recent years, with
distinctive features of their own.
</P>
<P>
During the 1993-1996 period, 78 billion yuan (about nine
billion US dollars) of capital were put into the construction of
small towns, with a total floor space of 200 million square meters
of newly constructed buildings, public facilities, and production
bases.
</P>
<P>
These small townships were built to develop the local economy,
and the small township's distinctive styles and characteristics
were formed during the building process.
</P>
<P>
Kejiao, a small town in Shaoxing County in east China's
Zhejiang Province, has been developed into the biggest trading
center for textile products in China since late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The large number of merchants and commodities coming into or
out of the town has contributed a lot to the rapid development of
its tertiary industry including restaurants, hotels,
transportation, financial, and recreational sectors.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 to the first half of 1996, the town has invested more
than 4.5 billion yuan (about 500 million US dollars) to complete
177 construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The population of the city has increased to more than 100,000,
and the town has become a market-oriented city, which has all the
facilities for convenient life and economic development.
</P>
<P>
Similar types of towns can also be found in other parts of
Zhejiang, such as the woolen sweater market in Puyuan in Tongxiang
County, the button market in Qiaotou in Yongjia County.
</P>
<P>
"Besides market-oriented towns, there are industrial towns in
Zhejiang, such as the Liushi in Leqing County for electrical
appliances, the Hengdian in Dongyang City for magnetic materials;
tourism towns such as Xikou in Fenghua City, Yaolin in Donglu
City, and Zhujiajian in Zhoushan City," said Zhang Qimei,
vice-governor of the province.
</P>
<P>
There are also towns in the province, whose development has
been attributed to their convenient communications access.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of small townships indicates the booming
of independent and separate regional economies in the province,
according to official analyses.
</P>
<P>
Statistics have shown that those booming townships have
attracted nearby township enterprises to develop around it, due to
its good investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The number of township enterprises in Zhejiang reached 902,000
in 1995, an increase of 82.6 percent over 1990. Most of those new
enterprises gathered around small towns, providing employment
opportunities for surplus rural labourers.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the Zhili township in Huzhou has drawn most of
the villagers around it to set up enterprises, leaving a number of
 farmers to cultivate the farmland under contract.
</P>
<P>
Those booming townships have built a group of cultural,
scientific, educational, health, and sports facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
