<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West African Peacekeepers Attack Freetown Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
forces, led by Nigerian troops, this morning started their
attacks at Sierra Leone's military coup leaders.
</P>
<P>
Heavy bombards and gunfire shook Sierra Leone's capital
Freetown at 6 a.m. (0600 gmt) as Nigerian naval vessels opened
fire from the sea.
</P>
<P>
"The attack has started," said an officer of the ECOMOG, the
forces of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS),
in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not make clear what were the targets and no
explosions were found near the coup leaders' headquarters.
Neither is there any sign of fighting on the ground.
</P>
<P>
The attack came a day after diplomats made a desperate attempt
to strike a peace agreement to end the crisis caused by the May
25 coup by junior officers to topple Sierra Leone's civilian
government led by President Ahmed Kabbah who is currently in
Canakry, capital of neighboring Guinea.
</P>
<P>
African states and the world community have been calling on
the coup soldiers to immediately hand back power over to
President Kabbah and go back to the barracks.
</P>
<P>
Pending failure of coup makers to accept the peace agreement,
the Nigeria-led ECOMOG forces threatened to intervene and force
the coup leaders out of power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
