<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Opens Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The 33rd Organisation of African
Unity (OAU) summit conference opens here today and high on the
agenda are conflicts in Africa, disputes between Libya and
the U.S., and Britain, the question of Palestine and the Middle
East, as well as Africa's economic issues.
</P>
<P>
According to a draft agenda released last night, the African
heads of state and government will discuss the situation in the
Great Lakes Region, specifically that in the Democratic Republic
of Congo and Burundi. Discussions will also centre on Liberia,
Sierra Leone, Somalia and Angola.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Council of Ministers, which ended here a few days
before, threatened to break what the ministers described as the "
unjust economic sanctions against Libya". The economic sanctions
had caused a lot of economic and social sufferings not only to
Libya but also to its neighbouring countries.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government will debate the question of
Palestine and the Middle East. The position taken by the Council
of Ministers meeting is that there can be no lasting and
comprehensive peace in the Middle East unless Israel withdraw
from all occupied Palestinian and Arab lands, including east
Jerusalem, the Syrian Golan Heights and southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
At least 27 heads of state and three prime ministers had
arrived by last night for the summit. Others were expected to
arrive here early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the leaders at the Harare International Airport,
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said, ''This is an honour and
challenge particularly at a time when the organisation is making
commendable progress in resolving conflicts and developing
strategies to improve the economies' integration.''
</P>
<P>
He hoped the summit would yield positive results in order to
further strengthen African cooperation and solidarity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
