<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Key to S. Africa's National Economy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has attached great importance to tourism which he
said occupies a "central place" in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, quoted by today's local newspaper Sowetan as saying
that tourism could earn as much as 4.5 billion U.S. Dollars a
year in foreign exchange and create over 800,000 jobs by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
"It is a powerful engine for job creation, economic revival and
will generate much-needed foreign currency," he said.
</P>
<P>
The South African president pointed out that expansion of the
tourism industry calls on the participation of all communities in
the country as well as nationwide respect for natural
environment.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has been creating an environment
that would make the country attractive for domestic and foreign
tourism operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
