<HEADLINE> Uganda To Set up Industrial Estates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 2 (Xinhua) --The Uganda Investment Authority
(UIA) decided to set up industrial estates near capital Kampala
in the next financial year, the local daily ''The Monitor''
reported today.
</P>
<P>
UIA is expected to release part of the 15 million U.S. Dollar
budget soon for the servicing of a vast piece of land of the
estates at Namanve.
</P>
<P>
According to UIA, the government is to spend 15 million dollars
on developing infrastructure on the land and initial plans on the
project will commence this financial year (1996/97).
</P>
<P>
UIA officials were quoted as saying that lack of serviced
industrial estates has over the years put the country at
disadvantage in wooing foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Neighbouring Kenya, said to be Uganda's main competitor as an
investment destination, commenced the provision of services
industrial land to investors a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that some prospective investors quit
because they cannot commit funds on reclaiming swamps in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Over 2,000 projects with planned investment worth 3.6 billion
dollars have been licensed since 1991 in Uganda. About 40 percent
of these projects are on the ground. 
</P>
</TEXT>
