<HEADLINE> Turkish President to Visit Egypt in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Ambassador to Egypt Yacar
Yakic said here Sunday evening that Turkey's President Suleyman
Demirel will visit Egypt in December.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a news conference after the last-minute
cancellation of Demirel's visit to Egypt in May sparked
speculation about growing grudge between the two countries due to
closer Turkish-Israeli strategic dialog.
</P>
<P>
"There is no misunderstanding between Cairo and Turkey and
consultations are at the highest level between the two sides,"
Yakic said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been demanding a Turkish explanation for planned
massive joint military drilling with Israel in the Mediterranean
this summer, which is reportedly targeted on Iran and Syria,
Israel's biggest foes.
</P>
<P>
Yakic defended the Turkish-Israeli military pact as "a
training agreement" that is not aimed at launching an alliance in
the region, noting that Turkey has similar agreements with some
other countries.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he stressed that no date has been set yet for the
three-way military games.
</P>
<P>
"The drills are for humanitarian considerations and are not
targeted against any country in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Turkish military operations in northern Iraq, the
ambassador said the incursions are not targeted against Iraq's
sovereignty but rather against the "terrorist" acts carried out by
the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
With the support of air bombing and artillery fire, about
25,000 to 50,000 Turkish troops have pushed across the border
into northern Iraq assaulting the PKK rebels since May 14.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League and other countries have asked Turkey to pull
its troops out of northern Iraq, a region that is still very
fragile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
