<HEADLINE> Burundi Hails OAU Decision to Soften Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Burundi welcomed the decision by
the OAU Council of Ministers meeting, which ended in Harare last
week, to moderate the economic sanctions imposed on its military
government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Burundi Foreign Minister Luc Rukingama said here on
Sunday that his government reaffirmed commitment to resolve the
crisis in the country in a peaceful way.
</P>
<P>
"It is hoped that there can be a speedy abolition of all
sanctions to promote stability in all of the countries of the
great lakes and the surrounding region," said the foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
Rukingama said his government's first mission was to endorse
President Pierre buyoya's decision to engage in negotiations with
various opposition armed groups.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations will be held in three phases: opening an
all-party meeting to find a peaceful solution to the crisis;
forging a new constitution; holding a national debate.
</P>
<P>
The Burundian foreign minister added the peace process was
currently being derailed by some armed groups which continued to
kill civilians, citing the opposition National Council for the
Defense of Democracy in Burundi as the main culprit.
</P>
<P>
"A lasting solution can only be found through enabling all
Burundians to improve the living standard in a peaceful and
stable environment, irrespective of their ethnic and political
backgrounds," said Rukingama.
</P>
<P>
He said his government would urge the incoming chairman of
OAU, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe to intensify efforts to
bring peace Burundi, ensure the sovereignty of every member
state by not interfering in their domestic affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
