<HEADLINE> Many Lusaka Buildings Illegal, Says Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Many buildings in Lusaka, the capital of
Zambia, are sub-standard and built without certification from
quolified architects, one Lusaka official has said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail today quoted Lusaka Province Deputy Minister
Sonny Mulenga as saying on Sunday that the majority of the
structures in the capital city are illegal in contravention of the law
which requires qualified architects to certify any building design
exceeding 120 square metres.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem is compounded by the shortage of building
inspectors at Lusaka City Council to make sure all buildings conformed
to this requirement.
</P>
<P>
"Many buildings of low standards have mushroomed in Lusaka in
breach of the law," said Mulenga.
</P>
<P>
