<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Region Values Cultivated Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Cultivated land in north China's
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, which has a high concentration of
Moslems, has increased by 22,346 hectares over the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
Though cultivated land area per capita in Ningxia is slightly
higher than the country's average, the imbalance between
overpopulation and scarce land still exists in the region: each
person there has 0.06 hectares of irrigated cultivated land.
</P>
<P>
To ensure grain output and economic development, the regional
government has provided favorable treatment for the development of
alkaline, barren or idle land over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
It has also encouraged people to plant fruit trees in
mountainous areas and dig fish ponds on beaches in order to
economize on the use of cultivated land.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the region has reformed land-use policies, imposing
more taxes on land developers. Since 1992, the region has
collected nearly 100 million yuan (about 12 million US dollars)
from land deals.
</P>
<P>
The region has also intensified law enforcement in the land
sector. Over the past decade, land management departments have
dealt with 6,102 cases, recovering 8.91 million square meters of
land.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Ningxia has set up basic farmland reserves in seven
cities and counties, putting more than 176,000 hectares of
farmland under top protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Indonesia's Ruling Party Sure of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- With the provisional results of
Indonesia's sixth general election announced, the ruling party
Golkar is sure to score a landslide victory, most probably the
biggest win in nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
In all the electorates nationwide, Golkar has won over 74
percent of the votes, enjoying clear advantages over its two
rivals, the United Development Party (PPP) and the Indonesian
Democratic Party (PDI).
</P>
<P>
At the moment, PPP, a Muslim-oriented group, has obtained
nearly 22.66 percent of the votes, about six percentages higher
than in 1992 election, while the PDI only gained 3.07 percent. In
1992, the PDI obtained 15 percent, up from 11 percent in the 1987
election.
</P>
<P>
The three parties contest for 425 seats of the 500-member House
of Representatives. The remaining 75 are reserved for the armed
forces whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
The final results are expected to be announced in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
During the May 29 election, the turnout was estimated at 90
percent or more of the 124.7 million eligible voters, according to
the General Election Institute.
</P>
<P>
Election Committee officials said the election was generally a
peaceful one despite some hitches which occurred in central and
eastern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here said it was not surprising for the
Golkar, with a membership of 35 million including the civil
servants, the armed forces, farmers and fishermen as well as
professional groups, to win the election this time as it had done
in the previous elections.
</P>
<P>
They said the economic growth averaging 7 percent a year for
the last two decades and the relatively low inflation in the
country under the leadership of Golkar gave the party a powerful
campaign platform.
</P>
<P>
The party leaders promised another similar growth in the second
long-term (25 years) development plan to propel Indonesia into the
ranks of the industrialized world in the middle of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The remarkable achievements of the poverty eradication program
launched by the Golkar government in recent years have also won
credibility for the party, said the analysts.
</P>
<P>
One of the most important achievements for the government was
made in the field of education. Widjojo Nitisastro, an outstanding
economist, said the success can be measured in terms of sharp
improvement in the literacy rate and the primary and secondary
school enrollment rate. All this added to a promising smooth start
of Indonesia's efforts to industrialize the economy by relying
more on quality human resources than to natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Presently there are 52 public universities and 1,284 private
ones in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said Golkar and PPP had both benefited from the
collapse of the PDI.
</P>
<P>
The PDI was bogged down in a leadership struggle after party
chief Megawati Soekarnoputri, eldest daughter of Indonesia's
founding president Soekarno, was ousted by a rival faction last
year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, political analysts said, her opponent, deputy
speaker of parliament Soerjadi, lacked credibility and the party
lost heavily.
</P>
<P>
Congratulating the Golkar victory, President Soeharto said,
"This earns us a credit to implement our long-term development
programs."
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said that Golkar, emerging with a stronger
mandate in this election, now faces the challenge of delivering
the many promises it made during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
One of its biggest challenges will be to eradicate corruption,
collusion and monopolies, Dean of the Socio-political Sciences
Faculty of the University of Indonesia Budiyatna said.
</P>
<P>
"The most interesting issue the poll contestants raised in
their platforms during the campaign was the fight against
corruption, collusion, manipulation and monopolies," he said.
Golkar has convinced voters that it would address these issues if
it won the election.
</P>
<P>
Oka Mahendra, a Golkar legislator, echoed this call. "Whoever
wins the election shouldn't be so intoxicated by victory that it
forgets its promises," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the country's election system, the 500 members of
the House of Representatives elected will form the People's
Consultative Assembly along with 500 appointed functional and
regional representatives. The People's Consultative Assembly next
year will elect the president and vice president and also
determine the guidelines of state policy for the term 1998-2003.
</P>
<P>
Analysts generally see the presidential poll in March next year
as the key election for the country, with keen interest in who the
76-year-old President Soeharto will select as a running mate and
potential successor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
