<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Philippine Market to See Slow Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine stock market
rebounded for the eighth consecutive trading day today, indicating
that the market is recovering gradually but slowly after weeks of
tumbles.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Stock Exchange composite index rose 11.27 points
to 2,820.72 on renewed confidence in the country's macro-economic
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
The market began to see a reversal a week ago amid rumors of
strong economic performance for the first quarter of this year.
But the tendency was strengthened after the government announced
last Thursday a 6.1 GNP increase for the period.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that although the growth rate was lower than the
government target of 6.4 percent for the first quarter due to a
manufacturing slowdown, it was deemed acceptable by investors in
general and reinstated that the country's fast growth pace is
sustainable.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said they remain confident that gross
national product (GNP) could grow by 7 percent to 8 percent in the
full year.
</P>
<P>
"The economy continued to grow at a comfortable healthy pace
contrary to initial negative market expectations," said Cielito
Habito, socio-economic planning secretary.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, the stock market suffered sharp declines a few weeks
ago on fears that the economy was on a serious downturn and would
soon follow the fate of Thailand, where a property crash, a
battered currency and a general economic slowdown led to a
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Such fears prompted investors, mostly foreigners, to flee the
market, hitting property and banking issues. In May, the main
index sank to a 17 month low before rising anew in a seven-day
up-swing towards the close of the month.
</P>
<P>
Closing the month strong, the composite index rebounded 161.28
points, or 6.09 percent to 2,809.45 after a four-week absence from
the 2,800 mark.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of this year, the property index
tumbled 17 percent while the overall market was down 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
To prevent a property-related financial crisis, the Central
Bank of the Philippines imposed a 20 percent limit on banks'
exposure to the property sector after the market plunged 4.5
percent on April 28, its biggest one-day drop in two years.
</P>
<P>
Now, analysts said, the first quarter economic growth figure
may have allayed the fears that the Philippines would become
another Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"The Thailand comparison was a big factor in the recent slump
of the market. The economic comparison growth figures showed that
we are not like Thailand and this improved the market's fragile
sentiment," said Allan Araullo, vice president at Regional Capital
Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
"There is still optimism on the whole because there is nothing
really fundamentally wrong with the economy, said James Lago,
analyst at Westin Securities Corp.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts are not convinced that the market is already
out of the woods after its recovery last month.
</P>
<P>
They said that the stock market is expected to rally this week
but trading will likely remain thin as foreign investors will
continue to stay away even after the release of relatively good
macro-economic numbers.
</P>
<P>
During the past week, foreign fund managers continued to stay
out of the bourse because of the attractive potential gains in
other markets such as the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Many foreign institutions which underrated the country will
not immediately return. If the second-quarter corporate earnings
show market improvement, they might come back," said Joel Mendoza,
research head of Santander Investment Securities (Phils), Inc..
</P>
<P>
But some analysts predicted that foreign players will buy into
the market soon as it is just a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
Economists here believe that the market's movement this month
will be mainly choppy, as investors will likely secure their gains
only after a short waiting period.
</P>
<P>
This is because the market is not waiting for any incentives
unraveling in the month, except for indications of second-quarter
earnings results, they said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, some analysts said, there might be some profit-taking
as investors may be tempted to adopt a sell-on-news strategy, but
after the temporary profit-taking the market will be on a solid,
sustainable rise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
