<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Begin Gas Export Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will next month start
exporting gas following the completion of the Escravos gas
project in Delta State, the Business Times newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The project, which costs 569 million U.S. Dollars, recently
completed and put into a test run. It is now ready for commercial
production, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Escravos is a project of the Chevron Nigeria Limited, a joint
venture between the U.S. oil company Chevron and the state-run
Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, when fully on stream, the project
will be able to gather 165 million cubic feet of gas daily for
processing from the company's Okan and Mefa oil fields.
</P>
<P>
The Escravos project was started six years ago and was
encouraged by the Nigerian government as the country's rich
natural gas resources are being daily flared into the air in
tremendous quantities in its many oil fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
