<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Pillar Industries Prop up Shanghai Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Six new pillar industries will
steer Shanghai's economic growth, turbocharging the motor of its
traditional industrial framework.
</P>
<P>
The booming pillars include automobile, electronics,
petrochemicals, iron and steel, and electrical appliances, whose
industrial output now accounts for more than half of the city's
total, said Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi today in an interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Each day, 213 fax machines, 548 automobiles, 1,200 motorbikes,
2,230 air-conditioners, 15,400 program-controlled telephones,
10,000-plus-kilowatt power units, and 30,000 tons of iron and
steel products are churned out by the pillar industries, which
have become a major pole of growth for the local economy.
</P>
<P>
The rise of the new pillars, resulting from new structural
optimizations, is a key factor behind the fast and steady
industrial growth in Shanghai, Mayor Xu said. Statistics indicates
that Shanghai industry grew at an annual average of 17 percent
during the 1992-1996 period, as opposed to only five percent in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's traditional pillar industries were textiles and
light industry. The city started pumping up technology-intensive
pillars with high added value, good economic efficiency, and
promising market potential in the early 1990. And the sector,
which received both policy support and cash input, witnessed a
rapid year-on-year growth rate of 20 percent in gross output
during the past five years, according to Xu Zhiyi, director of the
Municipal Economic Commission.
</P>
<P>
Every two seconds, a Santana sedan comes off the production
line. However, in the 1980s it took an hour to turn out one
automobile of the phased-out Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The new pillars now contribute 54.4 percent to
annually-increased industrial output value in Shanghai, while its
profits and taxes account for over 60 percent of the city's total,
said Xiong Lisheng, an expert with the Shanghai Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
While the six pillar industries are still at the height of
growth, Shanghai is already looking for new pillars to take hold
of advanced technology and sustain economic development. A new
generation of pillars, which include multi-media, bio-pharmacy,
new materials, micro-electronics, intelligent machine-building,
shipbuilding, and marine engineering, have been picked out as
choices, said an official with the Municipal Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The new generation of pillar industries will lay a solid
foundation for Shanghai leap into the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
