<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Blacks to Run Electricity Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 percent of all
managers, professionals and supervisors at the Eskom, the
national electricity utility in South Africa, will be black by
the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
Newly appointed company chairman Ruel Khoza told the
Enterprise Development Forum meeting held in Johannesburg over
the weekend that he wanted Africanness to reflect on Eskom's
affirmative action targets in five years' time.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Eskom would consider a strategic partnership, Khoza
said the feeling within the organization and the government was
that Eskom should "keep its door open".
</P>
<P>
He said his company was making active efforts to promote
cooperation with regional and neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"This (Eskom) is an organization posed to take on the world,
either single-handedly or with strategic partners, and win," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Eskom supplies 98 percent of electricity in South Africa and
is also dominating the southern African regional market. 
</P>
