<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Coupists Name Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) --Heavy bombardment eurpted in Sierra
Leone's capital of Freetown this morning as Nigerian-led west
African forces launched an attack on the coup leaders in S. Leone
</P>
<P>
The attack follows the failure of diplomats to desperately
strike a peace agreement to end the crisis caused by the May 25
coup and the announcement of the cabinet members by the coup
leader Major Jonny Paul Koroma, said reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Major Johnny Paul Koroma made public the cabinet list in
Freetown, capital of S. Leone on Sunday, defying the growing
international pressure on him to step down to give place to the
elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
According to reports today, Corporal Foday Sankoh, leader of
the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) which has been
fighting a civil war in the tiny west African country for the
last five years, has been appointed the deputy of Koroma.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, who is now in Nigeria alleged to be guest of the
Nigerian government, reportedly ordered his rebels to join the
new regime following the May 25 coup that toppled the elected
government led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Three other RUF rebels are also in the 20-member cabinet list.
</P>
<P>
Top level diplomatic efforts have been intensified in Freetown
to persuade the coup leaders to step down even as the United
States warned against any military action by the Nigeria-led west
African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between west African countries and the coup
leaders have been underway in Freetown since last Wednesday for a
peaceful settlement of the current crisis, aiming at restoring
Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that an estimated 3,000 ECOMOG soldiers
in Freetown surrounded the 1,800 rebel troops, including RUF
fighters. With the troop build up, ECOMOG has brought several
tanks, artillieries and personnel carriers into Freetown, to make
preparations for a possible attack, if talks fail.
</P>
<P>
Major Koroma has announced that his military regime firmly
opposed any intervention from outside.  
</P>
</TEXT>
