<HEADLINE> Syrian Vice President, FM Arrive in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim
Khaddam and Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara arrived here this
morning on a mission believed related with the deadlocked peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian officials are carrying a message from President
HafezAl-Assad to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents have been in close contacts with each other
in order to coordinate stances in restarting the Israeli-Syrian
peace track that has been frozen for over one year.
</P>
<P>
Syria, an important partner in the Mideast peace process, began
negotiations with Israel in 1991. But the sporadic talks broke
off last February after a spate of suicide bomb attacks in Israel
blamed on Palestinian extremists.
</P>
<P>
Syria said it will not return to the negotiating table with
the Israeli government unless it first agrees to pull out of the
Golan Heights, captured by the Jewish state in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu rejects the demand,
saying that the strategic plateau is vital to Israel. But his
predecessors, Labor Party leaders reportedly verbally accepted an
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan in return for normalized ties
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria favors a pan-Arab summit to make resolute decisions to
confront the Israeli settlement practice, which has led to the
stalemate in the Israeli-Palestinian peace track since two months
ago, but Egypt said such a move is premature.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first country to make peace with the Jewish state,
has been one of the key mediators in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
