<HEADLINE> Northeast China's Farmers Use Computers in Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Well-to-do farmers in northeast
China's Liaoning Province have turned to computers to manage rice
production.
</P>
<P>
Wang Quanfu, a farmer in the suburbs of the province's capital
city Shenyang, said that he uses a computer program to help
calculate the irrigation costs for his 0.83 hectares of
rice. Another 40 hectares of rice in his village are under
computer supervision.
</P>
<P>
With the use of computers in farming, villagers have cut their
water charges for irrigation for every hectare of rice by 75 yuan
(about nine US dollars). And they've reduced their electric costs
by 300 yuan each hectare.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thanks to computer planning, 750 kg. of rice has
been added to the per hectare yield, or adding 1,200 yuan more to
the profit.
</P>
<P>
The local government has spent nearly 200,000 yuan (about
24,000 US dollars) to spread the use of computers in farmland
irrigation, and the scale is expected to expand to 340 hectares of
rice this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
