<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Shanghai to Shine in Each Other's Company (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and Shanghai are
expected to shine together as international financial centers
after China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will complement each other rather than make each
other redundant, say experts today in interviews with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"I disagree with views that Shanghai would shake Hong Kong's
status as a major international financial center after July 1,"
says Dennis K W Wong, Vice President of the Shanghai Branch with
the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation. "What's
fundamental in their relationship is that they are mutually
complementary and their differences are clear-cut."
</P>
<P>
An international financial center, Hong Kong, where 85 of the
world's top 100 banking institutions have a residence, has
convertible currency. Hong Kong ranks the world's fifth in daily
trading of foreign exchange and seventh in foreign exchange
reserves and stock market.
</P>
<P>
Besides 16 Chinese banks, Shanghai, has branches of only 47
overseas banks, nine of which have just got approval for
conditionally doing business in Renminbi currency in the Pudong
New Area, says Wong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Shanghai to Shine in Each Other's Company (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the foreseeable future, the financial sector of Shanghai
will focus on inland operations, says Mao Yingliang, Governor of
the People's Bank of China Shanghai Branch. "So Shanghai's bid to
build itself into a world financial center will not undercut Hong
Kong's status. On the contrary, it will boost growth of Hong Kong
as an international financial center."
</P>
<P>
According to Mao, Shanghai will facilitate Hong Kong's status
as an international financial center in at least three aspects: an
increasing number of national financial markets such as inter-bank
lending, stock, foreign exchange, and insurance in Shanghai will
spur the influx of Hong Kong capital into Shanghai and inland
areas; the huge pool of capital in Shanghai provides for auxiliary
funds for overseas investment in China and Hong Kong may improve
its status if its financial institutions join hands with those in
Shanghai; with its expertise and a accurate reading of the market
pulse, Shanghai will be able to help Hong Kong's move into inland
markets.
</P>
<P>
International practices, effective management styles, and
managerial expertise, which are the keys to Hong Kong's success as
a world financial center, are guideposts for Shanghai's efforts to
build an international financial center and in these respects
Shanghai has much to learn from Hong Kong, says Jin Yun, President
of the Pudong Development Bank of Shanghai. "We hope to cooperate
with Hong Kong in training senior administrative personnel."
</P>
<P>
In fact, Hong Kong and Shanghai have had fruitful cooperation
in the financial area since the 1980s. While Hong Kong bankers
have opened businesses in Shanghai and helped bring Shanghai
closer to the international financial circles, those from Shanghai
have also set up offices in Hong Kong and many firms in Shanghai
have been listed on the Hong Kong Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
It's our firm belief that Hong Kong and Shanghai will join
hands to break new grounds in the financial sector and that the
two jewels will shine brilliantly with each other's light,
comments Anthony Neoh, Chairman of the Securities and Futures
Commission of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Further cooperation between Hong Kong and Shanghai after the
return of Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1 will contribute to
the uplifting of the financial status of both Hong Kong and
Shanghai, notes Zhao Qizheng, Vice Mayor of Shanghai. "With the
two lamps lit and shining together, the financial corridor on the
west bank of the Pacific Ocean will be more bright and brilliant,"
Zhao says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
