<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has short-listed 15 out
of 28 international applicants to rehabilitate oil tanks destroyed
in a twin attack by Tamil rebels on October 25, 1995 on oil
installations in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The 15 firms that have been short-listed are from Japan, South
Korea, China and India, according to Colombo authoritative sources
today.
</P>
<P>
The contract will be awarded at the end of this year while the
rehabilitation work is expected to commence in February next year
and the total refurbishing is expected to be completed in two
years.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank is to provide a credit of 24 million
U.S. dollars for the project.
</P>
<P>
During the rebel attack on Colombo's oil installations, eight
out of a total of 21 oil tanks were totally gutted. The financial
loss from the devastation is estimated at Rs 1,110 million (18.81
million dollars) comprising 9.32 million dollars for the repair of
the damaged tanks and 9.49 million dollars for the loss of damaged
property, according to the sources.  
