<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gujral Asks States to Set Up Special Courts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister I. K. Gujral is
reported to have written to state chief ministers to set up
special courts to try graft and bribery cases.
</P>
<P>
Gujral in a letter to the chief ministers has said corruption
has got into the root of the country's social, political and
economic system and should be firmly dealt with to root it out.
</P>
<P>
"The rampant corruption in different walks of life is
undermining the faith and confidence of people in democracy and
administration," he said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested going in for special courts to try those accused
of corruption as the normal courts take a lot of time in deciding
such cases. Unless such cases are decided speedily, the people
would treat the whole exercise of trying the guilty as an eyewash.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, the prime minister also wants the states to
strengthen the people's concern and awareness against corruption
through suitable campaigns and educative ventures. He felt that
urgent steps are needed to restore the people's faith and
confidence in the governance and rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Gujral also said corruption and climate of bribes are adversely
affecting the economic liberalization and national development.
"Development and corruption cannot go hand in hand," he stressed
in the letter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
