<HEADLINE> Liaoning Makes Artificial Rainfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a major grain
producer in northeast China, has artificially stimulated rainfall
to ease tension on drought-hit farmland.
</P>
<P>
With the help of two planes leased by the provincial government
and 85 high-angle guns which launched catalytic agents into cloud
layers on May 28, rain fell over about 70,000 square kilometers of
land space.
</P>
<P>
The meterological department estimated that at least 280
million tons of rain water fell, equal to the amount of two
large-sized reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
Since spring this year, Liaoning met with drought not seen
since the early 1950s. The rainfall was reduced by 20 to 80
percent in various parts of the province. The drought-hit farmland
reached 1.06 million hectares, and 150,000 farmers and 80,000
heads of cattle suffered from shortages of drinking water.
</P>
<P>
China began the practice of artificial rainfall in 1958. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
