<HEADLINE> Nepali Ruling Party Set to Win Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's major ruling party is on
its way to win a landslide victory in the local elections held
across the country last month, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Latest results of the local polls, held in two phases on May 17
and 26 respectively, showed that the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) is far ahead of other major
parties, according to the Election Commission here.
</P>
<P>
CPN-UML candidates have won in more than half of the country's
all local administration bodies as the polling results in most
local areas have been declared, a commission official said.
</P>
<P>
Final results of the local elections will come out in one or
two weeks as the polls in some villages and municipal wards have
been rescheduled due to election-related violence, the official
added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier CPN-UML President Man Mohan Adhikari said his party,
the biggest in Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand's three-party
coalition, would consider a mid-term parliamentary election if it
wins the local polls.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML would easily win a simple majority in the 205-seat
lower house in the next legislative election, a senior party
official said.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML's arch rival in the hung parliament, the main
opposition Nepali Congress (NC), has been suffering a popularity
debacle in recent years mainly due to frequent intra-party
infighting and the rampant corruption during its rule, political
analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
The NC, after having ruled the country for most of the time
since 1990 when Nepal adopted the multi-party parliamentary system
and controlled some two-thirds of the country's local bodies in
the past five years, is likely to be reduced to a second-front
player on the country's political arena, they said.
</P>
<P>
An NC-led three-party government collapsed last March after
losing a confidence vote, paying the way for the CPN-UML to join
the government led by Chand, a leader of the NC's former ruling
partner the National Democratic Party (RPP).
</P>
<P>
A mass procession and rally with the participation of some
senior CPN-UML leaders was organized here Sunday to celebrate its
candidates' victory in this capital city.
</P>
<P>
The party's candidates have won the seats of mayor and deputy
major in Kathmandu, which were taken by the NC in the last local
elections in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
