<HEADLINE> No Panic Purchasing in China This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Though the country experienced a
panic purchasing wave in the booming late 1980s, there will not be
such a nightmare this year when the national economy enters a new
round of rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
According to today's overseas version of the People's Daily,
the domestic market for consumption goods will maintain a stable
level in 1997, because the consumption trends of people show a
much higher diversity than ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
In order to prepare for housing and automobile purchases, most
urban residents will hardly put their savings into the market this
year. But, the domestic market for consumer goods will remain
active, as the demand for household electronic appliance rises in
cities and farmers' incomes increase steadily.
</P>
<P>
The supply of most industrial products will slightly exceed the
market demand. Agricultural produce, except for soy beans, will
also be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
The country's retail sales will increase by 18.6 percent, or
10.8 percent if adjusted for inflation, the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
