<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Government Acts to Curb Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- After the baht suffered a second
major speculation attack earlier this year, the Thai government
has stepped in to curb foreign speculation, demonstrating its
determination to safeguard the country's currency.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand called 36 commercial bank's treasurers for
a secret meeting in Bangkok on May 20, ordering them not to
provide any baht to foreign speculators.
</P>
<P>
The measure, called 'moral persuasion', seemed to help raise
the rate of the baht against the U.S. dollar after it was in
place, as many Thai financial institutions cut their credit lines
with their correspondent foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
Yet, some foreign bank branches in Thailand did not follow the
Thai central bank's order, saying it was not clear enough.
</P>
<P>
To clarify its position, the Thai central bank sent a letter on
May 28 to every financial institution to identify what
transactions that it did not want them to undertake with
non-resident financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The letter urged to stop lending baht in foreign exchange swaps
to non-residents, stop buying foreign currencies and selling baht
to non-residents, stop backing premature baht-dominated promissory
notes, bills of exchange, certificates of deposits and debt
instruments from foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also required financial institutions to report
every transaction conducted by non-residents to it every day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it stressed that normal transactions involving
imports, exports and equity investment would be allowed, but the
documents of these transactions must be kept for the central
bank's examination.
</P>
<P>
The bank indicated that the measures would be temporary and
limited to transactions which may lead to speculation on baht.
</P>
<P>
The baht was traded at around 25.80 against the dollar over the
past week after the measures were introduced, slightly up from the
rate of about 25.90 earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
In response to Thai central bank's move, foreign banks have
chosen to cut their credit lines with their Thai counterparts in
retaliation. Dealers said that Thailand may face a liquidity
shortage this week if the central bank does nothing.
</P>
<P>
Yet Thai officials assured foreign investors that the measures
would not affect normal foreign inflows of common international
trading and investment as they were introduced specifically
against speculators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
