<HEADLINE> Measles Outbreak in Singapore with 700 Cases in 1st </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Cases of measles increased
sharply in Singapore with more than 700 reported in the first five
months of this year, representing a seven-fold rise from more than
100 cases over the same period last year, the Straits Times said
today.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry reportedly said that this was the first
time in the last ten years or so that there has been such a steep
rise. About 45 percent of the reported cases were aged 15 and
above, and no deaths have been reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the jump was due to an accumulation of
adolescents and young adults who did not have measles before and
were not covered by the national childhood immunization program.
They are advised by the ministry to go to their family doctors or
polyclinics to be vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
Measles is an extremely contagious viral disease which spreads
through the air by droplets expelled by the infected person when
he sneezes or coughs.
</P>
<P>
Since the measles vaccine was first introduced here in 1976 and
immunization of all children aged between one and two was made
compulsory in 1985, cases of measles had dropped from 2,417 in
1984 to 146 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
This rate has since remained more or less constant, with only a
slight rise in 1992 and 1993. The ministry said its immunization
committee may consider introducing a second dose of measles
vaccine for children, which is the practice in Britain, the United
States and Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
