<HEADLINE> Riots Continue on Madura Island, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Riots in Madura island, Indonesia's
east Java province, continued Sunday morning while the election
institute agreed to repeat balloting in the island's two towns on
June 3, reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
A mob set ablaze a number of the local administrative offices
and houses. The house of a ruling party Golkar campaigner in
Pamekasan was set ablaze by unidentified persons Sunday morning,
said the reports.
</P>
<P>
They also burned and vandalized two sub-district offices and a
local education office.
</P>
<P>
The riots began soon after Thursday's (May 29) balloting in
which the United Development Party (PPP) supporters were
reportedly dissatisfied with the vote count. Police said that a
mob damaged the local administrative office, the house of a local
administrator and several shops and vehicles. 24 people were
detained, according to police.
</P>
<P>
However, PPP secretary general Tosary Widjaya said last Friday
the riots were provoked by the local election committee who did
not count the votes at the balloting booths. He added that the
party has filed a protest with the election committee proposing
that the Madurese towns be allowed to vote again.
</P>
<P>
The island of Madura is a Muslim stronghold and has thousands
of staunch supporters of the Muslim-led PPP.
</P>
<P>
The government has agreed to hold a repeat election at 121
polling stations on June 3 in Sampang and Pamekasan.
</P>
<P>
However, Suryatna Soebrata, secretary general of the General
Election Institute said, "The decision to repeat the voting is
purely the decision of the local election committee and has
nothing to do with the PPP protest."
</P>
<P>
Soebrata denied rumors that the riots were provoked by
officials who did not count the votes at the voting booths. They
took the ballot boxes to the local administrative office.
</P>
<P>
"The ballot boxes were taken away to secure them from public
attack. The election workers were simply trying to avoid
ballot-box stuffing," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to provisional results, Golkar has headed for another
landslide victory with more than 74 percent of the votes in its
favor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
