<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Per Capita GDP Projected to Exceed 30,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's per capita gross
domestic product (GDP) could surpass the 30,000-US-dollar mark
this year, overtaking the GDP figures in leading world economies
such as the United States and Germany, the Straits Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
This means the average Singaporean will be more productive this
year and contribute more to the economy than his American and
German counterparts, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Citing the World Competitiveness Yearbook 1997, just released
by the Swiss-based International Institute for Management
Development, it said that Singapore's per capita GDP stood at
28,472 US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
This placed Singapore in the eighth position, just behind
Germany and the United States, among the 46 economies studied by
the leading business institute.
</P>
<P>
The Straits Times projected that Singapore's per capita GDP
will surpass 30,000 US dollars this year, thus reaching a
significant milestone in the national economic development.
</P>
<P>
Assuming a seven percent growth for the economy, and accounting
for the natural increase in populations, the 30,000-US-dollar
figure would in fact be exceeded by a comfortable margin, it said.
</P>
<P>
Per capita GDP is the total of all goods and services produced
per person in an economy over a year. It is calculated in US
dollars at current prices and exchange rates to enable an
international comparison.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
