<HEADLINE> Coastal China Province to Tap Ocean Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The province of Fujian on China's
southeast coast plans to further tap the ocean's riches in the
coming 15 years, with ocean fishing taking up a large share of
that.
</P>
<P>
The province has announced its plan to bring its total aquatic
output to 5.85 million tons by the year 2010. As part of that, it
will expand the size of its tidal flats, improve fishing vessels,
and establish major aquatic products processing
plants. Preferential treatment policies are designed for foreign
companies who wish to invest in the projects.
</P>
<P>
For foreign-funded aquatic enterprises with at least a ten-year
contract, income tax exemptions will be given for two years,
according to the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises with a 15-year contract or longer will be exempt
from income tax for five years, beginning the year they start to
make a profit.  
</P>
