<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Helps With Ecological Balance (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some people have expressed concern that building a huge
reservoir on the river will aggravate the existing pollution
problems, as the speed of the water flow will be reduced. In
response, Huang said, "The Three Gorges Project itself is not a
pollutive project. Pollution existed throughout history."
</P>
<P>
Actually, he pointed out, the state put pollution control on
top agenda as when the project started, and control efforts will
be redoubled in five cities along the river, namely Luzhou, Yibin,
Chongqing, Fuling and Wanxian. The government has also shut down a
number of paper mills on the banks.
</P>
<P>
As for soil erosion that might be brought on alongside with
resettlement of residents, Huang said that it can be controlled as
long as the relocation program is well-planned and
implemented. And China has been successful in restoring vegetation
in dam areas.
</P>
<P>
The country is also building a shelter-forest and carrying out
a soil conservation project along the river, he said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent relocated farmers from rampant land reclaiming and
lumbering, the government will set up an agricultural system
friendly to the environment, which includes helping farmers
interplant crops and plant cash trees, and develop a diversified
economy in the local courtyards.
</P>
<P>
As for the protection of biological diversity, Huang said that
China has set up a nature reserve in the Dalaoling Mountain near
Yichang to protect ancestral plants unique to the reservoir area.
</P>
<P>
The country also plans to build landscape nature reserves in
Xingshan and Wushan. It will also set up a reserve on the upper
reaches to protect special fish species, a reserve on the middle
reaches to protect rare fish species, and one at the mouth of the
river to protect the Chinese sturgeon, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has set up an ecological and environmental
monitoring center to keep watch on unexpected effects the project
might have on the environment in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
