<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Revives as Susanti Signs Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, June 1 (Xinhua) -- With its success at the
World Championships, China revived to dominate the world badminton
again after a slump in the past several years.
</P>
<P>
Almost repeating their All England victories, the Oriental
power took three out of five golds available at the individual
championships after retaining the Sudirman Cup, which brings the
total number of their world titles to 21.
</P>
<P>
An awesome squad of Chinese women's singles players occupied
six berths in the last eight before teenager Gong Zhichao forced
Indonesia's Susi Susanti to sign off her last championships in a
losing note.
</P>
<P>
Ye Zhaoying ousted Susanti's heir-apparent Mia Audina in
another quarterfinal on her way to successful defence of her crown
taken at Lausanne, Switzerland, two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The supremacy could mean that in the years leading to the 2000
Olympic Games, there would probably be no challenger capable to
break the Chinese stronghold.
</P>
<P>
Susanti, an all-time legend who had won all major badminton
events in her career, said she could still play one more year but
that was still in question because she would need the consent from
her husband Allan Budi Kusuma.
</P>
<P>
Possibly the best all-round doubles player in the world, the
silent 21-year-old Ge Fei proved to be key to half of the Chinese
triumph.
</P>
<P>
Ge teammed up with Gu Jun to set the standard for any shuttler
when they completed a "Grand Slam" of the Olympic, World
Championships, All England, World Grand Prix Finals and the World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
After the retirement of reigning champion Gil Young Ah, their
position at the badminton worlds was so strong that no other pair
could even draw from them more than eight points in a whole match.
</P>
<P>
Ge's six-month parternership with Liu Yong also produced
stunning fruit in the mixed doubles, snatching every event they
competed this year. Even Denmark's 1995 champion-runnerup
combination could not stop them in the three-game final.
</P>
<P>
What could be the most noticeable fact here is the European, or
Danish to be more exact, encroachment on the Asians in the men's
singles.
</P>
<P>
Instead of only two quarter-final slots two years ago, the
Danish camp claimed four this time.
</P>
<P>
And most remarkably, the student doctor Peter Rasmussen
defeated a cramp-haunted Sun Jun for the first Danish title in 20
years.
</P>
<P>
The biggest regret here could be world number one Dong Jiong,
who was denied another grand show by influenza after injuries
forced him out two years ago.
</P>
<P>
With three more years to go for the Sydney Olympic Games, the
Chinese victories is no doubt a boost of morale.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Li Yongbo said, "I am elated to see our
contingent for Sydney became so matured here. I would say two
golds should not be very difficult."
</P>
<P>
The men's doubles is still the Indonesian teritory. Although
Ricky Subagja and Rexy Mainaky failed to repeat their Olympic
final victory over Malaysians Cheah Soon Kit and Yap Kim Hock in a
close semifinal, Candra Wijaya and Budiarto Sigit, considered out
of mould of Ricky and Rexy, carried on their torch to win the
final. 
</P>
