<HEADLINE> Volkswagen to Expand Tech-Center in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai Volkswagen Automotive
Co. Ltd, a Sino-German joint venture, will expand its existing
technical center to add independent product development capacity.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to retain the company's leading position
in China's car-making industry, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The expansion is expected to cost one billion yuan and to be
finished by 1998.  When completed, the center, which was set up
in 1994, will add a 1.4-meter proving ground, and a prototype and
test base, and greater capacities.
</P>
<P>
As one of the most successful joint ventures in China, Shanghai
Volkswagen Automotive produced has produced 800,000 Santana cars
so far. It sold more than 200,000 cars at a value of over 24
billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
The company won ISO9001 quality certificate in 1996, the first
auto-making business ever obtaining such a honor in China. Its
Santana cars held over 52 percent of China's car market share in
1996.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the local content rate of Santana LX had
reached 90.5 percent, compared with 2.7 percent in 1985, and the
local content rate with Santana 2000 had also climbed to 80
percent from 60 percent in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
