<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Send More Troops to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy will deploy more troops in
Albania to ensure that the parliament election will be held as
scheduled, Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who is on his third visit to Albania since riots
occurred early this year, told a news conference that his country
will send additional troops to Albania two weeks before the June
29 general election.
</P>
<P>
Italy has contributed 2,500 soldiers to the 6,300-strong
multinational force which is protecting the supply of aid
materials and maintaining law and order.
</P>
<P>
Italy will continue to offer material aid to the Albanian
police in collecting the weapons scattered in the society and send
more observers to supervise the parliament election, Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
While in Albania, Prodi inspected the multinational troops and
held in-depth discussions with Albanian President Sali Berisha and
Prime Minister Bashkim Fino on the details of the upcoming
election.
</P>
<P>
He told them that Italy will extensively participate in
Albania's reconstruction and encourage private investment there
only when all political forces have a good wish for a fair
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
