<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Helps With Ecological Balance (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Three Gorges Project, the
world's largest water-control endeavor, will create a new
ecological balance in the valley of the Yangtze River, according
to a Chinese environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
"The valley is in fact not ecologically balanced at present,
and the largest environmental problem is flooding," Dr. Huang
Zhenli told a seminar of the Young Scientists Forum held recently
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Other environmental problems which endanger the ecological
balance of the middle reaches of the river include soil erosion
and water pollution, he said.
</P>
<P>
Throughout history, the mighty river has frequently brought
disaster to its surrounding areas, said Huang, an official with
the Three Gorges Project Construction Commission of the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
In this century, three major floods have struck the "Mother
River," Huang said. Floods in 1931 and 1935 killed 145,000 and
142,000 people respectively. In 1954, another flood left more than
30,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
"The floods have not only caused heavy death tolls, but also
wreaked havoc on the ecological system in the valley," he said.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the Three Gorges Project will prevent similar
catastrophic floods, and slow the shrinkage of the country's
largest freshwater lake Dongting because of sand silting. At the
same time, the hydroelectric project will provide a clean energy
source.
</P>
<P>
It will also reduce infiltration of salty water into the river
mouth during the dry-water season, thereby improving water quality
in China's largest industrial and commercial center of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"In a word, the project will help set up an ecological balance
in the river valley, especially in the middle and upper reaches of
the river," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Wins 400m in Canet Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's Claudia Poll beat
Russian Denis Pankratov on Sunday at the Canet international
swimming meeting in Canet, France.
</P>
<P>
Poll, winner of Olympic 200 meters freestyle, clocked two world
bests of the season over the weekend, 1:58.18 in her favourite
event of the 200 meters and 4:10.56 in the 400 meter, reports said.
</P>
<P>
After badly missing an attempt at his own 200 meters butterfly
world mark on Saturday, Pankratov decided not to take part in
Sunday's 100 meters in order to return to Russia to prepare for
the European championships in Seville in August.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was hampered as most European swimmers seemed to be
concentrating on the big event. 
</P>
