<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malfeasance Investigation Bureau Set up in Hunan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A bureau to look into reports of
malfeasance has been established by the Hunan Provincial People's
Procuratorate in the central Chinese province as the first in
China dealing specifically with officials who are accused of
dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
It will act in parallel to the procuratorate's anti-corruption
bureau, to enhance fight against official misconduct, local
law-enforcement sources say.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, procuratorate departments in Hunan have had
some success in dealing with malfeasance cases, and investigated
1,065 last year.
</P>
<P>
Local sources say that the anti-corruption bureau has helped
penalize those who committed economic crimes, but that crimes
involving dereliction of duty have not been contained.
</P>
<P>
With the revision of China's Criminal Law by the top
legislature in March this year, the definition of dereliction of
duty has broadened to apply to 32 actions instead of 15, local
officials say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
