<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Deadline for Rural Firms to Meet Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China has set a deadline for rural
firms to meet high standards in production and quality control,
according to a report.
</P>
<P>
The state has urged more than half of the major industrial
products from rural enterprises in eastern areas and 30 percent of
the major products from western regions to reach international
standards or advanced foreign standards within five years, China
Daily said today.
</P>
<P>
But officials acknowleged that governments at all levels,
especially those of the country's 2,143 counties and county-level
cities, have to make "tremendous efforts" to reach the goal, the
English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
County economies are becoming an important part of the national
economy, with the total output value of rural industries reaching
44 percent of the country's total in 1995, statistics indicated.
</P>
<P>
But before 1995, about one-third of the products from
industrial enterprises in rural areas were made without definite
technical standards, said Li Chuanqing, director of the State
Bureau of Technical Supervision (SBTS), China's watchdog of
standardization, metrology and quality control.
</P>
<P>
This has seriously affected the quality of products and the
growth of economic efficiency of rural enterprises, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Li said the bureau launched an experiment to raise the
standard and quality of production in 103 counties in early 1995
and has made initial success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Tough on Gold Panning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- For years, farmers living by the
Lushuijiang River could not irrigate their land with the
poor-quality water, which worsened by the day as the result of
ambitious gold-diggers and their diesel-driven panning boats.
</P>
<P>
"The river was on the verge of ruination," says one indignant
villager from the poverty-stricken Longan County.
</P>
<P>
Now, after strict government action to control illegal panning
practices, the river water runs clear and local farmers are
delighted with their harvests.
</P>
<P>
Most heavily affected was the Xinguang section of the river,
near the Longhushan Natural Reserve in southwest China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, about one hundred km. away from the
region's capital city of Nanning.
</P>
<P>
Villagers say it's hard to imagine the time when there were
more than 120 boats panning for gold floating on a section within 3.7
km. of the river with 70-plus diesel engines and over 3,000
gold-diggers on board.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the content of gold in every cubic meter
of sand in this section of the river reaches 0.3 to 0.5 grams, and
the purity of the gold is especially high.
</P>
<P>
But haphazard panning wreaked havoc on the river water and
surrounding land.
</P>
<P>
"Sand piles had emerged above the water surface, blocking up
the river," said Huang Huisong, secretary of the Longan County
Committee of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
The riverbank was nearly destroyed, as was about 83 mu (about
5.5 hectares) of farmland. Meanwhile, the irrigation of more than
25,000 mu (about 1,667 hectares) of land was seriously affected.
</P>
<P>
"The water quality deteriorated greatly, and the natural
landscape of the nearby natural reserve also received some
damage," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, in compliance with state law, the regional and
county governments put a stop to all damaging panning
activities. Government officials confiscated and dismantled all
equipment of law-breakers who continued to pan.
</P>
<P>
And to further aid the financially-troubled county, the local
government has spent 120,000 yuan (about 15,000 US dollars) to
dredge the river and help resume the cultivation of the devastated
farmland.
</P>
<P>
"We have planted spring corn on 27 mu of the recovered land,"
Huang said, adding that most of the environmental reclamation work
is finished, and the government is now focusing on improving the
local ecology.
</P>
<P>
Action has been taken to stop illegal panning in several other
cities in the county, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unleaded Petrol Now Available in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- About 292 gas stations in Beijing
started selling unleaded petrol yesterday.
</P>
<P>
By January 1, 1998, the city's 700 gas stations, including
those in rural areas, will have no alternative but to sell
unleaded fuel.
</P>
<P>
Ye Junlong, assistant at a gas station in Xicheng District,
gave each of his customers information about the pollution that
leaded fuel causes and where they can change their old fuel
tickets into new ones.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the customers have known about this, and they don't
care that much about the price increase," Ye said.
</P>
<P>
The price for unleaded petrol 90 and 93 is 2.23 yuan (0.27 US
dollars) and 2.4 yuan (0.29 US dollars) per litre, 0.11 yuan
(0.013 US dollars) and 0.16 yuan (0.019 US dollars) more expensive
than leaded fuel.
</P>
<P>
"We have been selling unleaded petrol for more than a
fortnight," Ye said.
</P>
<P>
One customer said it is more convenient for him since his car
can only use unleaded fuel.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Guohua, a taxi driver, said it will cost him 120 yuan
(14.5 US dollars) more on fuel each month.
</P>
<P>
"Cleaner air is worth the price since my studio is right in the
open," Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
The move is necessary to reduce lead content in the air. It is
also important to install catalytic converters in motor vehicles
to clean exhaust emissions.
</P>
<P>
Unleaded petrol producers must get ready to supply 1.17 million
cars in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Chief Urged to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary Renato
de Villa has been urged to resign from his post after he announced
his plan to run for the Presidency in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, leaders of Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino
(Laban), the biggest opposition party in the country, demanded on
Sunday the quit of de Villa, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
De Villa, one of the possible nominees of President Fidel
Ramos, declared over the weekend that he would run under the
ruling Lakas party banner in 1998 and would not seek nomination
outside Lakas.
</P>
<P>
"Since he has formally declared his plan to join Lakas and run
for President next year, Secretary de Villa should resign form the
Ramos Cabinet", the statement said.
</P>
<P>
De Villa should heed the call of Lakas Senator Leticia Shahani
who urged Lakas leaders holding key party positions to relinquish
their posts to level the playing field in the selection of Lakas'
candidate in 1998, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the early resignation of de Villa would also
prevent the military chief from using government sources to
advance his 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
Besides the defense portfolio, de Villa also chairs the
National Peace and Order Council and the National Disaster
Coordinating Center, which oversees the government's relief and
rehabilitation efforts in calamity-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
De Villa has to join Lakas first before he gets the support of
the president. Ramos' apointment was reportedly a guarantee of
success in the 1998 elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
