<HEADLINE> Bailey Wins Match Race As Johnson Stops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Donovan Bailey, the Olympic
gold medalist at 100 meters, beat American Michael Johnson to win
their 150-meter match race in 14.99 seconds in Toronto Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The unofficial 150-meter world mark of 14.93 seconds was set in
1993 by Britain's John Regis.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, the 200- and 400-meter champion in the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics, stopped running midway through due to a leg cramp,
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
"I had a problem with cramping in the curve," Johnson was
quoted as saying. "I ignored the importance of the injury."
</P>
<P>
Bailey, running in front of a raucous home crowd at SkyDome,
won 1 million U.S. dollars in the One on One Challenge of
Champions.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian never looked like anything but a winner as he
burst out of the blocks and was well ahead halfway around the 75
meter curve.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after that, Johnson gave up, dropping into a jog, then
a walk, then stopping, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Despite Johnson's triumph, the lack of a full-speed finish was
a disappointment to a crowd of about 40,000 people at SkyDome
indoor stadium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
