<HEADLINE> Ge, Gu Make Badminton Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China's Ge Fei and Gu Jun
made badminton history at the world championships here on Sunday
when they beat fellow countrywomen Qin Yiyuan and Tang Yongshu to
win the women's doubles final.
</P>
<P>
They became the first ever women's duo to complete a "Grand
Slam" of the Olympic, World Championships, All England, World
Grand Prix Finals and the World Cup competitions.
</P>
<P>
Their 15-1, 15-8 win over teammates also gave Ge Fei her second
gold medal at the championships after she paired with Liu Yong to
win the mixed doubles final on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
She was the only shuttler at this championships who made the
feat.
</P>
<P>
Tang and Qin took the women's doubles silver medal. China's
Qian Hong and Liu Lu and Indonesia's Rosiana Zelin and Eliza
shared the bronze medals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ye Retains Women's Singles Title at Badminton Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China's Ye Zhaoying
retained her world women's singles title after beating fellow
countrywomen Gong Zhichao 12-11, 11-8 in the world badminton
championships final here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Gong Zhichao took the silver medal. Another two Chinese Wang
Chen and Han Jingna were both placed third.
</P>
<P>
"I was so happy today. It was hard to beat any of my teammates
because they knew my style so well," Ye told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
After they tied the first game 9-9 to go into the setting, Gong
reached the game point at 11-9 but Ye staged a comeback to take
the game.
</P>
<P>
Ye, who beat Gong in 12 minutes to win the All England Open
this March, met few trouble in the second game and scrolled to her
second consecutive world title.
</P>
<P>
"It was harder to play a national championships than an
international event," said Ye after the 45-minute match. "I
thought I would have a 50-50 chance in today's match."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the role of her teammates here, Ye said, "They
hold their post well."
</P>
<P>
Two Indonesians were knocked out the quarter-finals by the
Chinese, with Wang beating Mia Audina and Gong disposing of Susi
Susanti.
</P>
<P>
Ye, 23, said she is now preparing for the badminton competition
at National Games in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
