<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard and Leader of the Opposition Kim
Beazley are expected to meet this week in an effort to reduce the
risk of a divisive double dissolution election on federal race
powers.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- An audacious 616 million US dollar plan has emerged to renew
hope that Sydney's most hated building, the apartment complex at
East Circular Quay, can be torn down, in an attempt to reopen the
panoramic views to the Opera House and Royal Botanical Gardens.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard yesterday accused the Opposition
of hypocrisy over its calls for compensation for aboriginal stolen
children, saying the Labor Party had opposed making payments while
in government. About 100,000 aboriginal children were forcibly
removed from their families under the nation's infamous
assimilation policies during 1910-1970.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government has decided to cap payments of the
616 million US dollar diesel fuel rebate to mining companies,
sparking strong protests from the industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
