<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daughter of Le Pen Loses in Legislative Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Marie-Caroline Le Pen, the daughter
of the leader of the extreme-right National Front (FN) Jean Marie
Le Pen, today lost the legislative election, winning 24.09 percent
of votes in her constituency in Mantes-la-Jolie near Paris.
</P>
<P>
Socialist candidate Annette Peulvast-Bergeal, whom Le Pen
personally harassed and hit with fists during a campaign clash
last week, won the election with 40.29 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the FN mayor of Toulon, Jean-Marie Le Chevallier,
today became the only parliament deputy to represent the extreme
right party in the National Assembly by winning the election in
his constituency of the southern department of Var.
</P>
<P>
After the outcome of the legislative election was published, Le
Pen again called on President Jacques Chirac to resign.
</P>
<P>
"Jacques Chirac played quit or double. He lost. He was beaten
twice in majority of suffrage for the first and in the seats for
the second," said Le Pen.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the former center-right majority is now
eating the bitter fruit of "diabolizing the FN."
</P>
<P>
The FN, which won a record high of 15 percent of votes in the
first round of the election, could from now on take advantage of
the failure of the center-right coalition by luring support from
the partisans of the right. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Majority Does Not Promise Moon to French People: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- French Socialist chief Lionel Jospin,
coming victorious from the legislative election, said this evening
that the new leftwing parliament majority does not promise a moon
to the French people, but will meet their reasonable and realistic
demands.
</P>
<P>
Calling all the leftwing forces "forces of change" which have
"crowned" the legislative election, he congratulated the partisans
of the Socialist Party, the Communist Party, the Movement of
Citizens, the Greens and radical socialists on their victory.
</P>
<P>
"Beyond the happiness felt by me and many others this evening,
the strong feeling that this very important election inspired in
me is that of a profound demand which comes from our people," said
Jospin in his declaration after primary projections declared a
clear victory by the leftist parties.
</P>
<P>
He said that the demand is not for a miracle that no one
believes, but one which is "reasonable and pressing for the real
progress in a period of time for the Frenchwomen and Frenchmen,
particularly for the least favored among them."
</P>
<P>
He said that the French people are demanding "justice, a
profound renovation of public life and our democracy, an economic
and social policy to be implanted for the service of man, a
reorientation of the European construction to which we will hold
on, and a scrupulous attention to the problems met by the French
people in their daily life."
</P>
<P>
He said that the leftist majority will meet the demands by
listening to the citizens, holding dialogue with them and
proposing new and realistic measures to realize their wishes.
</P>
<P>
"We would have the obligation to mobilize all our energy, all
our heart, all our competence, to put into work this different
policy for which the new majority has just been elected," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
