<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Bailey Beats Johnson in One-to-One Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Olympic gold medal sprinter
Donovan Bailey beat his U.S. rival Michael Johnson in a one-to-one
race in Toronto today.
</P>
<P>
Bailey was the first to finish the 150-meter track in 14.99
seconds, while U.S. sprinter Michael Johnson failed to reach the
end.
</P>
<P>
The pullout by Johnson proved that "he was a chicken," an
excited Bailey told the CBC Television, which broadcast live the
race.
</P>
<P>
It also exposed Johnson's "weakness" and he was afraid to lose,
Canada's Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
The winner stressed that he had "never any doubt" that he
himself is the fastest man in the world.
</P>
<P>
Bailey got the title of the world's fastest man, and 1.5
million U.S. dollars. The loser got a paltry 500,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Today's race was supposedly to settle the debate over who is
the fastest man in the world.
</P>
<P>
Bailey set the world record and won the gold medal in the 100
meters at last year's Summer Olympic Games in Atlanta, while
Johnson became the first male Olympian to win both the 200- and
400-meter races.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the games, there has been a controversy as to who is
really "the world's fastest man."
</P>
<P>
The Canadians say the title should go to Bailey, since
traditionally the title has always belonged to the current world
or Olympic champion in the 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the U.S. insists that Johnson has every reason to have
access to that title.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, Bailey and Johnson announced that they
would participate in the race which was over 150 meters on a
curved track, midway between Bailey's 100-meter event and
Johnson's 200. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
