<DOCNO> XIE19970602.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mitterrand's Prophecy on Quick Socialist Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- When former French President Francois
Mitterrand was lying in his deathbed, he left this prophecy: "You
will see that the left will return more quickly than one can think
of."
</P>
<P>
Today, the former Socialist president's prophecy has come true,
as the Socialist Party scored a clear majority in the National
Assembly today after living only four years as a minority.
</P>
<P>
Another thing Mitterrand did for his party was that he
handpicked Lionel Jospin, today's Socialist chief of France, as
the first secretary of the party in 1981.
</P>
<P>
"He is capable of fulfilling the highest functions," Mitterrand
once said of Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Jospin, the 59-year-old Socialist chief, who will be the next
French prime minister with the back-up of a left parliament
majority, strikes one first of all as a strict college professor
who can win the confidence of his students with his sincerity,
patience and steadfastness.
</P>
<P>
Born in Meudon near Paris, Jospin was from a family worshipping
the Protestant Church. His father, a school teacher, devoted his
life to teaching handicapped children, and his mother was a
mid-wife.
</P>
<P>
"I was a good child, but I lost much of my time playing and
running after girls, doing sports and organizing student unions.
What interests me is not competition, but life itself," he said.
</P>
<P>
Holder of a doctorate degree of political science from the
prestigious Ecole Nationale d'Administration, Jospin formally
entered the political stage of France in June 1981 by winning the
parliamentary election in Paris.
</P>
<P>
While holding parliament deputy's posts for Paris and the
southwestern department of Haute-Garonne in the 1980s, he also
served as minister of state and minister of education, scientific
research and sport under two Socialist prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
In February 1995, Jospin presented himself as the candidate for
the presidential election after Jacques Delors quit the race. He
proved his capability by raising the support rate of his party
from 23 percent to 47.3 percent within three months.
</P>
<P>
He reorganized the Socialist Party after the defeat in the 1995
presidential election, and presented a whole set of policies on
European construction, employment, social and economic strategies,
democracy and institutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
Tirelessly running this legislative campaign over the past one
month by meeting people everywhere and appearing on television
frequently, Jospin won support from the voters with his warm
humane sincerity, a character strikingly different from his rival,
Alain Juppe.
</P>
<P>
Jospin publicly opposes the American style market force
economic theory, and calls for a reorientation of European
construction, promotion of social justice, renovation of public
life and a socio-economic policy which serves the interests of the
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
